<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let
<ul>
<li>
<m>R</m> be a finite region in the <m>xy</m>-plane,
</li>
<li><p>
the boundary, <m>C</m>, of <m>R</m> consist of a single piecewise smooth, simple closed curve
    <ul>
<li>
     that is oriented (i.e. an arrow is put on <m>C</m>) consistently
     with <m>R</m> in the sense that if you walk along
     <m>C</m> in the direction of the arrow, then <m>R</m> is on your left
</li>
</ul></p>

<sidebyside width="27%">
  <image source="pfigs/greens1"/>
</sidebyside>
</li>
<li>
<m>F_1(x,y)</m> and <m>F_2(x,y)</m> have continuous first partial derivatives
at every point of <m>R</m>.
</li>
</ul>
Use Stokes' theorem to show that
<me>
\oint_{C} \big[F_1(x,y)\,\dee{x} +F_2(x,y)\,\dee{y}\big]
 =\dblInt_{R}\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
                - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}\Big)\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
</me>
i.e. to show Green's theorem.
</p>

</statement>

<hint><p>
Define the vector field <m>\vF(x,y,z) = F_1(x,y)\,\hi +F_2(x,y)\,\hj</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
See the solution.
</p></answer>

<solution><p> Think of the <m>xy</m>-plane as being the plane <m>z=0</m> in <m>\bbbr^3</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="37%">
  <image source="pfigs/stokesGreen"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
    We are going to apply Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>) with <m>S</m> being the given region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane
and with <m>\vF(x,y,z) = F_1(x,y)\,\hi +F_2(x,y)\,\hj</m>.
Then
<ul>
<li>
the unit normal vector to <m>S</m> specified in Stokes theorem is <m>\hk</m>
(if you walk along <m>\partial S = C</m> in the direction of the arrow
    on <m>C</m> with the vector from your feet to your head  having direction <m>\hk</m>
    then <m>S=R</m> is on your left hand side) and
</li>
<li>
<m>\dee{S}=\dee{x}\,\dee{y}</m> and
</li>
<li> the curl of <m>\vF</m> is
<me>
\vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{z} \\
                  F_1(x,y) &amp; F_2(x,y) &amp; 0 \end{matrix}\right]
=\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
                - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}\Big)\,\hk
</me>
</li>
</ul>
So Stokes' theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_{C} \big[F_1(x,y)\,\dee{x} +F_2(x,y)\,\dee{y}\big]
&amp;=\oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
  =\dblInt_{S}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\ \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{R}\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
                - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}\Big)\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Verify the identity
<m>\ \oint_C\phi\vnabla\psi\cdot \dee{\vr}=-\oint_C\psi\vnabla\phi\cdot
                       \dee{\vr}\ </m>
for any continuously differentiable scalar fields <m>\phi</m> and <m>\psi</m> and
curve <m>C</m> that is the boundary of a piecewise smooth surface.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
First verify the vector identity
<m>\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]=\vZero</m>
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
See the solution.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We are to show that <m>\oint_C[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m>.
 Suppose that <m>C=\partial S</m>. Then, by Stokes' theorem
<me>
\oint_C[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_S\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]\cdot\hn\, \dee{S}
</me>
We will show below
that <m>\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]=\vZero</m>.
This will imply that <m>\oint_C[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]\cdot \dee{\vr}=\vZero</m>.
One way to see that <m>\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]=\vZero</m>
is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]
&amp;=\vnabla\times[\vnabla(\phi\psi)] &amp;
&amp; (\text{by part (c) of Theorem }<xref ref="thm_gradIdentities"/>)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\vZero&amp;
&amp; (\text{by part (b) of Theorem }<xref ref="thm_degTwoIdentities"/>)
</mrow>
</md>
Another way to see that <m>\vnabla\times[\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]=\vZero</m>
is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\!\times\![\phi\vnabla\psi+\psi\vnabla\phi]
&amp;=\vnabla\phi\!\times\!\vnabla\psi+\phi\vnabla\!\times\!(\vnabla\psi)
+\vnabla\psi\!\times\!\vnabla\phi+\psi\vnabla\!\times\!(\vnabla\phi)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\vnabla\phi\times\vnabla\psi
+\vnabla\psi\times\vnabla\phi
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in\text{since } \phi\vnabla\times(\vnabla\psi)=\psi\vnabla\times(\vnabla\phi)=\vZero
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\vZero
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>
