<exercise>
<statement><p>
 Let <m>C</m> be the curve of intersection of the cylinder <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>
and the surface <m>z=y^2</m> oriented in the counterclockwise direction as seen
from <m>(0,0,100)</m>. Let <m>\vF=(x^2-y\,,\,y^2+x\,,\,1)</m>. Calculate
<m>\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>
<ol marker="a">
<li> by direct evaluation
</li>
<li> by using Stokes' Theorem.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
To parametrize the curve <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, <m>z=y^2</m>, first parametrize the
circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>. That is, find <m>x(t)</m> and
<m>y(t)</m> obeying <m>x(t^2)+y(t)^2=1</m>. Then set <m>z(t) =y(t)^2</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>2\pi</m> </p><p>
(b) <m>2\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) Observe that <m>x(t)=\cos t</m> and <m>y(t)=\sin t</m> obey <m>x(t)^2+y(t)^2=1</m>.
Then <m>z(t)=y(t)^2=\sin ^2 t</m>.  So we may parametrize the curve by
<m>\vr(t)=(\cos t, \sin t, \sin^2 t)</m> with <m>0\le t\le 2\pi</m>.
Then
<md>
<mrow>
\vr'(t)&amp;=(-\sin t\,,\, \cos t \,,\, 2\sin t\cos t)
</mrow><mrow>
\vF\big(\vr(t)\big)&amp;=\big(\cos^2t-\sin t\,,\,\sin^2t+\cos t\,,\,1\big)
</mrow><mrow>
\vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\vr'(t)&amp;=-\sin t\cos^2 t+\sin^2 t+\sin^2t\cos t
+\cos^2t+2\sin t\cos t
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=1+\frac{1}{3}\diff{}{t}[\cos^3t+\sin^3 t]+\sin(2t)
</mrow><mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}
\left\{1+\frac{1}{3}\diff{}{t}[\cos^3t+\sin^3 t]+\sin(2t)\right\}\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\left[t+\frac{1}{3}[\cos^3t+\sin^3 t] -\frac{1}{2}\cos(2t) \right]_0^{2\pi}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b) Let <m>S</m> be the surface <m>z=f(x,y)</m> with <m>f(x,y)=y^2</m>
and <m>x^2+y^2\le 1</m>. Since <m>C</m> is oriented counter clockwise when
viewed from high on the <m>z</m>-axis, Stokes' theorem requires that we use
the normal <m>\hn</m> to <m>S</m> with positive <m>z</m> component. Hence
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\,dS&amp;=\Big[-\pdiff{f}{x}\,\hi
-\pdiff{f}{y}\,\hj+\hk\Big]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
=\Big[-2y\,\hj+\hk\Big]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{z} \\
                  x^2-y &amp; y^2+x &amp; 1 \end{matrix}\right]
=2\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,dS&amp;=2\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=2\dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 1}\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Evaluate
 <m>\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m> where <m>\vF=ye^x\,\hi+(x+e^x)\,\hj+z^2\,\hk</m> and
<m>C</m> is the curve
<me>
\vr(t)=(1+\cos t)\,\hi+(1+\sin t)\,\hj+(1-\sin t-\cos t)\,\hk\qquad
0\le t\le 2\pi
</me>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Apply Stokes' theorem.
Note that <m>\vr(t) = x(t)\,\hi+y(t)\,\hj +z(t)\,\hk</m>
obeys <m>x(t)+y(t)+z(t)=3</m>, for every <m>t</m>, and that <m>x(t)\,\hi+y(t)\,\hj
=(1+\cos t)\,\hi+(1+\sin t)\,\hj</m> runs counterclockwise around
the circle of radius 1 centered on <m>(1,1)</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We apply Stokes' theorem. First,
<me>
\vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \pdiff{}{x} &amp;  \pdiff{}{y} &amp; \pdiff{}{z} \\
                  ye^x &amp; x+e^x &amp; z^2
                 \end{matrix}\right]
=\big(1+e^x-e^x\big)\,\hk
=\hk
</me>
Note that <m>\vr(t) = x(t)\,\hi+y(t)\,\hj +z(t)\,\hk</m>
obeys <m>x(t)+y(t)+z(t)=3</m>, for every <m>t</m>, and that <m>x(t)\,\hi+y(t)\,\hj
=(1+\cos t)\,\hi+(1+\sin t)\,\hj</m> runs counterclockwise around
the circle of radius 1 centered on <m>(1,1)</m>. So we choose <m>S</m>
to be the part of the plane <m>G(x,y,z)=x+y+z=3</m> with <m>(x-1)^2+(y-1)^2\le 1</m>.
Then, by Stokes' Theorem,
<me>
\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
=\dblInt_S \hk\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
</me>
with
<me>
\hn\,\dee{S} = \pm \frac{\vnabla G}{\vnabla G\cdot\hk}\,\dee{x} \dee{y}
= \pm\big(\hi+\hj+\hk\big)\,\dee{x} \dee{y}
</me>
As <m>(1+\cos t)\,\hi+(1+\sin t)\,\hj</m> runs counterclockwise around
the circle <m>(x-1)^2+(y-1)^2\le 1</m>, Stokes' theorem
specifies the plus sign and
<me>
\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_{(x-1)^2+(y-1)^2\le 1} \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
=\pi
</me>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2011A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Find the value of
<m>\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}</m> where
<m>\vF = \big(z - y\,,\, x\,,\, -x\big)</m> and <m>S</m> is the hemisphere
<me>
\Set{(x, y, z) \in\bbbr^3 }{ x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 4,\ z \ge 0}
</me>
oriented so the surface normals point away from the centre of the
hemisphere.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The form of the integral should be quite suggestive.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>8\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The boundary of <m>S</m> is
<me>
\partial S = \Set{(x,y,z)}{z=0,\ x^2+y^2=4}
</me>
and can be parametrized
<me>
\vr(\theta) = 2\cos\theta\,\hi +2\sin\theta\,\hj\qquad
0\le\theta\le 2\pi
</me>
</p>

<sidebyside width="28%">
<image source="pfigs/OE11A_4"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
So, by Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>)
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_0^{2\pi} (\overbrace{-2\sin\theta\,\hi+2\cos\theta\,\hj-2\cos\theta\,\hk}^
               {\vF(\vr(\theta))})\cdot
     (\overbrace{-2\sin\theta\,\hi+2\cos\theta\,\hj}^
                {\vr'(\theta)})\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=4\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=8\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 1998D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
 Let <m>\cS</m> be the part of the surface <m>z=16-{(x^2+y^2)}^2</m>
which lies above the <m>xy</m>-plane. Let <m>\vF</m> be the vector field
<me>
\vF=x\ln(1+z)\,\hi+x(3+y)\,\hj+y\cos z\,\hk
</me>
Calculate
<me>
\dblInt_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</me>
where <m>\hn</m> is the upward normal on <m>\cS</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The form of the integral should be quite suggestive.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>12\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The boundary of <m>\cS</m> is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>, <m>z=0</m>.
Let <m>\cC</m> be this circle, oriented by the parametrization <m>x(t)=2\cos t</m>,
<m>y(t)=2\sin t</m>, <m>z(t)=0</m>. By Stokes' theorem
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\dblInt_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\int_0^{2\pi}\vF(2\cos t,2\sin t,0)\cdot \diff{\vr}{t}(t)\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in=\int_0^{2\pi}\big[0\,\hi+2\cos t(3+2\sin t)\,\hj+2\sin t\,\hk\big]\cdot
\big[-2\sin t\,\hi+2\cos t\hj\big]\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in=\int_0^{2\pi}\big[12\cos^2 t+8\cos^2t\sin t\big]\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in=\int_0^{2\pi}\big[6+6\cos(2t)+8\cos^2t\sin t\big]\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in=\Big[6t+3\sin(2t) -\frac{8}{3}\cos^3 t\Big]_0^{2\pi}
=12\pi
</mrow>
</md>
For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
<m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2 t\,\dee{t}</m>, see Example
<xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
</p>
</solution>

<solution>
<p>
<ul>
<li>
<m>\cS</m> be the surface specified in the question, with upward pointing normal, and
</li>
<li>
<m>\cD</m> be the disk <m>\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\le 4,\ z=0}</m>, with normal <m>\hn=\hk</m>, and
</li>
<li>
<m>\cC</m> be the circle <m>\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2=4,\ z=0}</m>, oriented as in the figure below.
</li>
</ul>
</p>

<sidebyside width="27%">
<image source="pfigs/OE98D_6"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Note that <m>\cC</m> is the boundary curve for both <m>\cS</m> and <m>\cD</m>. So, by
Stokes' theorem, twice
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;=\int_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_{\cD}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{\cD}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hk\,\dee{S}
</mrow>
</md>
Now the <m>\hk</m> component of <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hk
&amp;=\pdiff{}{x}\big[x(3+y)\big]
 - \pdiff{}{y}\big[x\ln(1+z)\big]
=3+y
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>As <m>y</m> is odd under <m>y\rightarrow-y</m> and <m>\cD</m> is invariant under <m>y\rightarrow-y</m>, we have <m>\dblInt_{\cD}y\,\dee{S}=0</m>
and
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_{\cS}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
= \dblInt_{\cD}(3+y)\,\dee{S}
=3\dblInt_{\cD}\dee{S}
=3\,\text{Area}(\cS) =3\,\pi 2^2=12\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2001A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\cC</m> be the intersection of the paraboloid <m>z=4-x^2-y^2</m>
with the cylinder <m>x^2+(y-1)^2=1</m>, oriented counterclockwise when viewed
from high on the <m>z</m>-axis. Let <m>\vF=xz\,\hi+x\,\hj+yz\,\hk</m>. Find
<m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
What's the title of this section?
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Let <m>S</m> be the portion of the paraboloid <m>z=f(x,y)=4-x^2-y^2</m>
with <m>x^2+(y-1)^2\le 1</m> and let <m>\hn</m> be the upward normal to <m>S</m>.
For this surface
<me>
\hn\,\dee{S}=\big(-f_x(x,y)\,\hi -f_y(x,y)\,\hj +\hk\big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
   = \big(2x\,\hi+2y\,\hj+\hk\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</me>
by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>). As <m>(x,y,z)</m> runs over
<m>S</m>, <m>(x,y)</m> runs over the circular disk
<me>
D = \Set{(x,y)}{x^2+(y-1)^2\le 1}
</me>
For the given vector field
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
xz &amp; x &amp; yz
\end{matrix}
\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=z\,\hi+x\,\hj+\hk
</mrow>
</md>
so that, by Stokes' theorem  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_D
   \big[2x\overbrace{(4-x^2-y^2)}^{z=f(x,y)}+2xy+1\big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
By oddness under <m>x\rightarrow -x</m>, all terms integrate to zero except
for the last. So
<me>
\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_D\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
=\text{Area}(D)
=\pi
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vF = - ye^z\,\hi + x^3\cos z\,\hj + z\sin(xy)\,\hk</m>, and let
<m>S</m> be the part of the surface <m> z = (1-x^2)(1-y^2)</m> that lies above the
square <m>-1\le x\le 1</m>, <m>-1\le y\le 1</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane.  Find
the flux of <m>\vnabla\times \vF</m> upward through <m>S</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
We are to evaluate a flux integral of the form <m>\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}</m>. Sure looks like
one side of Stokes' theorem.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>8</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The surface
<md>
<mrow>
S&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{-1\le x\le 1,\ -1\le y\le 1,\ z\ge 0,\ z = (1-x^2)(1-y^2)}
</mrow><mrow>
 &amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{-1\le x\le 1,\ -1\le y\le 1,\ \ z = (1-x^2)(1-y^2)}
</mrow>
</md>
Note that when <m>x=1</m> or <m>x=-1</m> or <m>y=1</m> or <m>y=-1</m>,
we have <m>z= (1-x^2)(1-y^2)=0</m>.  So the boundary of <m>S</m>,  call it <m>C</m>,
is the boundary of the square <m>-1\le x,y\le 1</m>, <m>z=0</m>, oriented
counterclockwise. Here is a sketch of <m>C</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="36%">
<image source="pfigs/singGnA"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Apply Stokes' theorem. Observing that <m>z=0</m> on <m>C</m>
so that <m>\vF = -y\,\hi +x^3\,\hj</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\oint_C[-y\,\hi+x^3\hj]\cdot \dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\underbrace{\int_{-1}^1 -(-1)\,\dee{x}}_{y=-1{\rm\ side}}
   +\underbrace{\int_{-1}^1 (1)^3\,\dee{y}}_{x=1{\rm\ side}}
   + \underbrace{\int^{-1}_1 -(1)\,\dee{x}}_{y=1{\rm\ side}}
   + \underbrace{\int^{-1}_1 (-1)^3\,\dee{y}}_{x=-1{\rm\ side}}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=8
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Evaluate the integral   <m>\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>, in which
<m>\vF = (e^{x^2} - yz\,,\,\sin y - yz \,,\,xz + 2y)</m> and <m>C</m>
is the triangular path from <m>(1, 0, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 1, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 0, 1)</m> to
<m>(1, 0, 0)</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The vector field <m>\vF</m> looks too complicated for a direct evaluation
of the line integral. So, try Stokes' theorem.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>1</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We shall apply Stokes' Theorem. The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{z} \\
                  e^{x^2} - yz &amp; \sin y - yz &amp; xz + 2y\end{matrix}\right|
</mrow><mrow>&amp;=(2+y)\,\hi-(z+y)\,\hj+(0+z)\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
The curve <m>C</m> is a triangle. All three vertices of the triangle obey
<m>x+y+z=1</m>. So the triangle is the boundary
of the surface <m>S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x\ge 0,\ y\ge 0,\ z=1-x-y\ge 0}</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="23%">
<image source="pfigs/domainTriangleA"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
The equation of the surface is <m>z=f(x,y)=1-x-y</m>.
So, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\ \dee{S}
&amp;=\big(-f_x\,\hi-f_y\,\hj+\hk\big)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=(\hi+\hj+\hk)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
Here <m>\hn</m> is the upward pointing unit normal.
The set of points <m>(x,y)</m> for which there is a corresponding <m>(x,y,z)</m>
in <m>S</m> is  <m>T=\Set{(x,y)}{x\ge 0,\ y\ge 0,\ x+y\le 1}</m>, which is a triangle
of area <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
Since 
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;=[(2+y)\hi-(z+y)\hj+(0+z)\hk]\cdot(\hi+\hj+\hk)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= 2\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
we have
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}&amp;=\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_T 2\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
= 2\,\text{Area}(T)
=1
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2001D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vF(x,y,z)=-z\,\hi+x\,\hj+y\,\hk</m> be a vector field. Use
Stokes' theorem to evaluate the line integral
<m>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
</m>
where <m>C</m> is the intersection of the plane <m>z=y</m> and the ellipsoid
<m>\frac{x^2}{4}+\frac{y^2}{2}+\frac{z^2}{2}=1</m>, oriented
counter-clockwise when viewed from high on the  <m>z</m>-axis.
</p>

</statement>

<answer><p>
<m>4\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Stokes' theorem, which is Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>, says that <m>\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_S\nabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}</m> for any surface <m>S</m> whose boundary is
<m>C</m>. For the given vector field
<md>
<mrow>
\nabla\times\vF(x,y,z)
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
-z &amp; x &amp; y
\end{matrix}
\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi-\hj+\hk
</mrow>
</md>
Choose
<md>
<mrow>
S &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{z=y,\ \tfrac{x^2}{4}+\tfrac{y^2}{2}+\tfrac{z^2}{2}\le 1}
</mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{z=y,\ \tfrac{x^2}{4}+y^2\le 1}
</mrow>
</md>
to be the part of the plane <m>z=y</m> bounded by the ellipsoid.
</p>

<sidebyside width="71%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE01DQ4"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
As <m>S</m> is part of the plane <m>z=f(x,y)=y</m>, (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>), gives that
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\,\dee{S} &amp;=\pm \big(-f_x\,,\,-f_y\,,\, 1\big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\pm (0\,,\,-1\,,\, 1)\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
As <m>C</m> has the standard orientation (counter-clockwise when viewed
from high on the <m>z</m>-axis), we want <m>\hn</m> to have a positive <m>z</m>-component.
So
<m>\hn\,\dee{S}= (0\,,\,-1\,,\, 1)\dee{x}\dee{y} </m>.
From the second form of <m>S</m> given above, we see that as <m>(x,y,z)</m>
runs over <m>S</m>, <m>(x,y)</m> runs over
<me>
D=\Set{(x,y)}{\tfrac{x^2}{4}+y^2\le 1}
</me>
Consequently, Stokes' theorem gives that
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}

&amp;=\dblInt_D\overbrace{(1,-1,1)}^{\nabla\times\vF}\cdot
            \overbrace{(0\,,\,-1\,,\, 1)\dee{x}\dee{y} }^{\hn\,\dee{S}}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\dblInt_D \dee{x}\dee{y}
=2\,\text{Area}(D)
</mrow>
</md>
The ellipse <m>D</m>, that is <m>\tfrac{x^2}{4}+y^2\le 1</m>, has semi-axes
<m>a=2</m> and <m>b=1</m> and hence area <m>\pi ab=2\pi</m>. Finally
<me>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=2\,\text{Area}(D)
=4\pi
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2016D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Consider the vector field <m>\vF(x,y, z) = z^2 \,\hi + x^2 \,\hj + y^2\,\hk</m>
in <m>\bbbr^3</m>.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Compute the line integral <m>I_1 = \int_{C_1}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>
where <m>C_1</m> is the curve consisting of three line segments,
<m>L_1</m> from <m>(2, 0, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 2, 0)</m>, then
<m>L_2</m> from <m>(0, 2, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 0, 2)</m>, finally
<m>L_3</m> from <m>(0, 0, 2)</m> to <m>(2, 0, 0)</m>.
</li>
<li>
A simple closed curve <m>C_2</m> lies on the plane <m>E\,:\, x + y + z = 2</m>,
enclosing a region <m>R</m> on the plane of area <m>3</m>, and oriented in a
counterclockwise direction as observed from the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
Compute the line integral <m>I_2 = \int_{C_2}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>8</m></p><p>
(b) <m>4\sqrt{3}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Note that the curve of part (a) is a simple closed curve
that lies in the plane <m>x+y+z=2</m> and is oriented in a
counterclockwise direction as observed from the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
The curve of part (a) encloses a triangle.
</p>

<sidebyside width="40%">
<image source="pfigs/OE16D_9"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Two of the sides of the triangle
are <m>(0,2,0)-(2,0,0)=(-2,2,0)</m> and  <m>(0,0,2)-(0,2,0)=(0,-2,2)</m> so the
area of the triangle is
<me>
\frac{1}{2}\big|(-2,2,0)\times (0,-2,2)\big|
=\frac{1}{2} \det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\\
     -2&amp; 2&amp; 0 \\  0 &amp; -2 &amp; 2 \end{matrix}\right]
=\frac{1}{2}\big|(4,4,4)\big|
=2\sqrt{3}
</me>
So let's do part (b) first.
</p>

<p>(b) We are not told explicitly what <m>C_2</m> is, so we certainly can't
do a direct evaluation. Instead, let's use Stokes' theorem
(Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>). The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
z^2 &amp; x^2 &amp; y^2
\end{matrix}
\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= 2y\,\hi
    +2z\,\hj
    +2x\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
The upward pointing unit normal to <m>E</m> is <m>\hn=\frac{\hi+\hj+\hk}{\sqrt{3}}</m>.
So, by Stokes' theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
I_2 &amp;= \int_{C_2}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
    =\dblInt_R \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;    =\dblInt_R \big(2y\,\hi +2z\,\hj +2x\,\hk\big)\cdot
               \frac{\hi+\hj+\hk}{\sqrt{3}}\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\dblInt_R \big(\overbrace{y + z + x}^
                             {=2\ {\rm on}\ R}\big)\,\dee{S}

=\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\text{Area}(R)
=4\sqrt{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(a) Denote by <m>T</m> the triangle enclosed by <m>C_1</m>. By the
computation that we have just done in part (b)
<md>
<mrow>
I_1 &amp;= \int_{C_1}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
     =\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\text{Area}(T)
     =8
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2017A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>C = C_1 + C_2 + C_3</m> be the curve given by the union of the
three parameterized curves
<md alignment="alignat">
<mrow>
\vr_1(t) &amp;= \big(2\cos t, 2\sin t, 0\big), &amp;\qquad
&amp;0 \le t \le \pi/2
</mrow><mrow>
\vr_2(t) &amp;= \big(0, 2\cos t, 2\sin t\big), &amp;
&amp;0 \le t \le \pi/2
</mrow><mrow>
\vr_3(t) &amp;= \big(2\sin t, 0, 2\cos t\big), &amp;
&amp;0 \le t \le \pi/2
</mrow>
</md>
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Draw a picture of <m>C</m>. Clearly mark each of the curves <m>C_1</m>, <m>C_2</m>, and <m>C_3</m>
and indicate the orientations given by the parameterizations.
</li>
<li>
Find and parameterize an oriented surface <m>S</m> whose boundary is <m>C</m>
(with the given orientations).
</li>
<li>
Compute the line integral <m>\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> where
<me>
\vF = \Big(y + \sin(x^2)\,,\, z - 3x + \ln(1 + y^2)\,,\, y + e^{z^2}\Big)
</me>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer>
<p>(a)</p>
<sidebyside width="40%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE17A_5"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
(b) <m>S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2=4,\ x\ge 0,\ y\ge 0,\ z\ge 0}</m>
with
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\vr(\theta,\varphi)
= 2\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \hi
+ 2\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \hj
+ 2\cos\varphi\ \hk
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;0\le\theta\le\frac{\pi}{2},\
0\le\varphi\le\frac{\pi}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
and
<me>
\hn = \cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \hi
            +\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \hj
            +\cos\varphi\ \hk
=\frac{1}{2}\,\vr(\theta,\varphi)
</me>
</p>

<p>(c) <m>-4\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) Observe that
<ul>
<li>
the curve <m>C_1</m> is one quarter of a circle in the <m>xy</m>-plane,
centred on the origin, of radius <m>2</m>, starting at <m>(2,0,0)</m> and
ending at <m>(0,2,0)</m> and
</li>
<li>
the curve <m>C_2</m> is one quarter of a circle in the <m>yz</m>-plane,
centred on the origin, of radius <m>2</m>, starting at <m>(0,2,0)</m> and
ending at <m>(0,0,2)</m> and
</li>
<li>
the curve <m>C_3</m> is one quarter of a circle in the <m>xz</m>-plane,
centred on the origin, of radius <m>2</m>, starting at <m>(0,0,2)</m> and
ending at <m>(2,0,0)</m>.
</li>
</ul>
Here is a sketch.
</p>
<sidebyside width="40%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE17A_5"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
(b) <m>C</m> lies completely on the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=4</m>. So it is natural
to choose
<me>
S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2=4,\ x\ge 0,\ y\ge 0,\ z\ge 0}
</me>
and to parametrize <m>S</m> using spherical coordinates
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\vr(\theta,\varphi)
= 2\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \hi
+ 2\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \hj
+ 2\cos\varphi\ \hk
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;0\le\theta\le\frac{\pi}{2},\
0\le\varphi\le\frac{\pi}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
Since
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}
&amp;= -2\sin\theta\sin\varphi\,\hi +2\cos\theta\sin\varphi\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\varphi}
&amp;= 2\cos\theta\cos\varphi\,\hi +2\sin\theta\cos\varphi\,\hj
  - 2\sin\varphi\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
so that
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}\times\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\varphi}
&amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix} \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
-2\sin\theta\sin\varphi &amp; 2\cos\theta\sin\varphi &amp; 0 \\
2\cos\theta\cos\varphi &amp; 2\sin\theta\cos\varphi &amp; - 2\sin\varphi
         \end{matrix}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -4\cos\theta\sin^2\varphi\ \hi
   -4\sin\theta\sin^2\varphi\ \hj
   -4\sin\varphi\cos\varphi\ \hk
</mrow>
</md>
(<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>) gives
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\,\dee{S} &amp;= \pm \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}\times
            \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial\varphi}\,\dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \mp 4\big(\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \hi
            +\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \hj
            +\cos\varphi\ \hk\big)
          \sin\varphi\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
</mrow>
</md>
We want <m>\hn</m> to point outward, for compatibility with the orientation
of <m>C</m>. So we choose the <m>+</m> sign.
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= 4\big(\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \hi
            +\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \hj
            +\cos\varphi\ \hk\big)
          \sin\varphi\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\,\vr(\theta,\varphi)\sin\varphi\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(c) The vector field <m>\vF</m> looks too complicated for a direct evaluation
of the line integral. So, in preparation for an application of Stokes'
theorem, we compute
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\\
     \frac{\partial }{\partial x}&amp;
        \frac{\partial }{\partial y}&amp;
        \frac{\partial }{\partial z}\\
 y + \sin(x^2) &amp; z - 3x + \ln(1 + y^2) &amp; y + e^{z^2}\end{matrix}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -4\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
So, by Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.1in= \int_0^{\pi/2}\hskip-5pt\dee{\varphi}
                         \int_0^{\pi/2}\hskip-5pt\dee{\theta}\
\big(-4\hk\big)\cdot
\big(\cos\theta\sin\varphi\ \hi
            +\sin\theta\sin\varphi\ \hj
            +\cos\varphi\ \hk\big)\
          4\sin\varphi
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.1in=-16 \int_0^{\pi/2}\dee{\varphi}\int_0^{\pi/2}\dee{\theta}\
              \cos\varphi\sin\varphi
=16\ \frac{\pi}{2}\ \frac{\cos^2\varphi}{2}\bigg|_0^{\pi/2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.1in=-4\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2016A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
We consider the cone with equation <m>z = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}</m>. Note that its tip,
or vertex, is located at the origin <m>(0, 0, 0)</m>. The cone is oriented
in such a way that the normal vectors point downwards (and away from
the <m>z</m> axis). In the parts below, both <m>S_1</m> and <m>S_2</m> are
oriented this way.
</p>

<p>Let <m>\vF = \big(-zy, zx, xy \cos(yz)\big)</m>.
</p>

<p><ol marker="a">
<li>
Let <m>S_1</m> be the part of the cone that lies between the planes
<m>z = 0</m> and <m>z = 4</m>. Note that <m>S_1</m> does not include any part of
the plane <m>z = 4</m>. Use Stokes' theorem to determine the value of
<me>
\dblInt_{S_1} \vnabla\times\vF \cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
</me>
Make a sketch indicating the orientations of <m>S_1</m> and of the
contour(s) of integration.
</li>
<li>
Let <m>S_2</m> be the part of the cone that lies below the plane
<m>z = 4</m> and above <m>z = 1</m>. Note that <m>S_2</m> does not include any part
of the planes <m>z = 1</m> and <m>z = 4</m>. Determine the flux of <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> across <m>S_2</m>. Justify your answer, including a sketch indicating the
orientations of <m>S_2</m> and of the contour(s) of integration.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>-128\pi</m>,</p><p>
(b) <m>-126\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
 (a)
The boundary, <m>\partial S_1</m>, of <m>S_1</m> as specified in Stokes' theorem (Theorem
<xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>) is the circle
<m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=4</m>, <m>z=4</m> oriented <em>clockwise</em> when viewed from high on
the <m>z</m>-axis. That is, we can parametrize <m>\partial S_1</m> by
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t) = 4\cos t\,\hi -4\sin t\,\hj +4\,\hk,\qquad 0\le t\le 2\pi
</mrow>
</md>
So
<md>
<mrow>
\vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;= \big(16\sin t \,,\, 16\cos t \,,\, -16\sin t\cos t \cos(-16\sin t)  \big)
</mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2in
      \cdot
   \big(-4\sin t \,,\, -4\cos t \,,\, 0\big)\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -64\,\dee{t}
</mrow>
</md>
and, by Stokes' theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_{S_1} \vnabla\times\vF \cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= \oint_{\partial S_1} \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
= -64 \int_0^{2\pi} \dee{t}
=-128\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<sidebyside widths="26% 29%" valign="middle">
  <image source="pfigs/conePa"/>
 <image source="pfigs/conePb"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
 (b)
The boundary, <m>\partial S_2</m>, of <m>S_2</m> consists of two parts,
a circle in the plane <m>z=4</m> and a circle in the plane <m>z=1</m>.
We'll call the first part <m>\partial S_{2a}</m>. It is the same as
<m>\partial S_1</m>. We'll call the second part <m>\partial S_{2b}</m>.
It is the circle <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=1</m>, <m>z=1</m> oriented <em>counterclockwise</em>
when viewed from high on the <m>z</m>-axis.
We can parametrize it
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t) = \cos t\,\hi +\sin t\,\hj + \hk,\qquad 0\le t\le 2\pi
</mrow>
</md>
So, on <m>\partial S_{2b}</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;= \big(-\sin t \,,\, \cos t \,,\, \sin t\cos t \cos(\sin t)  \big)
      \cdot
   \big(-\sin t \,,\, \cos t \,,\, 0\big)\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \dee{t}
</mrow>
</md>
and, by Stokes' theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_{S_2} \vnabla\times\vF \cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= \oint_{\partial S_{2a}} \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
   +\oint_{\partial S_{2b}} \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -128\pi +  \int_0^{2\pi} \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-126\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2015A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Consider the curve <m>C</m> that is the intersection of the plane <m>z = x + 4</m>
and the cylinder <m>x^2 + y^2 = 4</m>, and suppose <m>C</m> is oriented so that
it is traversed <em>clockwise</em> as seen from above.
</p>

<p>Let <m>\vF(x, y, z) = \big(x^3 + 2y\,,\, \sin(y) + z\,,\, x + \sin(z^2)\big)</m>.
</p>

<p>Use Stokes' Theorem to evaluate the line integral
<m>\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>4\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Denote by
<me>
S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{z=x+4,\ x^2+y^2\le 4}
</me>
the part of the plane <m>z=x+4</m> that is contained in the cylinder
<m>x^2+y^2=4</m>. Orient <m>S</m> by the downward pointing normal
<m>\hn =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(1,0,-1)</m>. Then <m>C</m> is the boundary of <m>S</m>.
The part of <m>C</m> and <m>S</m> that are in the first octant are sketched below.
</p>

<sidebyside width="45%">
 <image source="pfigs/OE15A_5"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
We may parametrize <m>S</m> by
<me>
\vr(x,y) = (x,y, x+4)\qquad\text{with}\quad x^2+y^2\le 4
</me>
So,
<me>
\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial x}\times\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial y}
= \det\left[\begin{matrix} \hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \end{matrix}\right]
= \big(-1, 0, 1\big)
</me>
and, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\,\dee{S} = -\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial x}\times
            \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial y}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
= (1,0,-1)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
We have chosen to <q><m>-</m></q> sign in <m>\hn\,\dee{S} =
       \pm\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial x}\times
        \frac{\partial\vr}{\partial y}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}</m>
to give the downward pointing normal. As the curl of <m>\vF</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
x^3 + 2y &amp; \sin(y) + z &amp;  x + \sin(z^2)
\end{matrix}
\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -\hi -\hj -2\hk
</mrow>
</md>
Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>) gives
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\dblInt_S (-1,-1,-2)\cdot(1,0,-1)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_S \dee{x}\dee{y}
=4\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Consider the vector field <m>\vF(x, y, z) = (x+y^2\,,\, 2y+4z^2\,,\,3z+2x^2)</m> in
<m>\bbbr^3</m>. Compute the line integral <m>\oint_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>, where
<m>C</m> is the curve consisting of the three line segments,
<m>L_1</m> from <m>(2, 0, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 2, 0)</m>, then
<m>L_2</m> from <m>(0, 2, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 0, 1)</m>, and finally
<m>L_3</m> from <m>(0, 0, 1)</m> to <m>(2, 0, 0)</m>.
</li>
<li>
A simple closed curve <m>C</m> lies in the plane <m>x + y + 2z = 2</m>.
The surface this curve <m>C</m> surrounds inside the plane <m>x + y + 2z = 2</m>
has area <m>6</m>. The curve <m>C</m> is oriented in a counterclockwise
direction as observed from the positive x-axis.
Compute the line integral <m>\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m> , where <m>\vF</m>
is as in (a).
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
All three vertices of part (a) lie in the plane of part (b).
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) -8</p><p>
(b) <m>-8\sqrt{6}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) Note that all three vertices, <m>(2,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,2,0)</m> and <m>(0,0,1)</m>, lie in the
plane <m>x+y+2z=2</m>. So the entire path lies in that plane too.
</p>

<sidebyside width="38%">
<image source="pfigs/OE13DB_4"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
In part (b)
we will need to evaluate a line integral that clearly cannot be computed
directly <mdash/> we will need to use Stokes' theorem. So let's use
Stokes' theorem in part (a) too. First, we find
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
x+y^2 &amp; 2y+4z^2 &amp; 3z+2x^2
\end{matrix}
\right]
=-8z\,\hi - 4x\,\hj - 2y\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
Let <m>S</m> be the triangular surface that is contained in the plane
<m>x+y+2z=2</m> and is bounded by <m>L_1</m>, <m>L_2</m> and <m>L_3</m>. Orient <m>S</m> by the normal vector <m>\hn = \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}(\hi+\hj+2\hk)</m>. Then,
<me>
\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn
=\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\big(-8z\,\hi - 4x\,\hj - 2y\,\hk\big)\cdot(\hi+\hj+2\hk)
=-\frac{4}{\sqrt{6}}(x+y+2z)
</me>
and, by Stokes' theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=-\frac{4}{\sqrt{6}}\dblInt_S(x+y+2z)\,\dee{S}
=-\frac{8}{\sqrt{6}}\dblInt_S\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\frac{8}{\sqrt{6}}\text{Area}(S)
</mrow>
</md>
The triangle <m>S</m> is half of the prallelogram with sides <m>(0,2,0)-(2,0,0)
=(-2,2,0)</m> and <m>(0,0,1)-(2,0,0)=(-2,0,1)</m>. The area of the parallelogram
is
<md>
<mrow>
\big|(-2,2,0)\times (-2,0,1)\big|
=\big|(2,2,4)\big|
=2\sqrt{6}
</mrow>
</md>
So
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr} = -\frac{8}{\sqrt{6}} \sqrt{6}
=-8
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p> (b)
Let <m>\tilde S</m> be the specified surface. Then, as in part (a),
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_{\tilde S}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=-\frac{4}{\sqrt{6}}\dblInt_{\tilde S}(x+y+2z)\,\dee{S}
=-\frac{8}{\sqrt{6}}\dblInt_{\tilde S}\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\frac{8}{\sqrt{6}}\text{Area}(\tilde S)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-8\sqrt{6}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2009A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Evaluate the line integral
<me>
\int_C\left(z+\frac{1}{1+z}\right)\dee{x}
         +xz\,\dee{y}
         +\left(3xy-\frac{x}{(z+1)^2}\right)\dee{z}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is the curve parameterized by
<me>
\vr(t) = \big(\cos t\,,\, \sin t\,,\, 1 - \cos^2 t \sin t\big)\qquad
0 \le t \le 2\pi
</me>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The curve <m>C</m> is the boundary of a surface. To guess the surface
express the <m>z</m> component of <m>\vr(t)</m> in terms of the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> components.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>5\pi/4</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
 Let's try Stokes' theorem with
<me>
\vF = \left(z+\frac{1}{1+z}\right)\hi
         +xz\,\hj
         +\left(3xy-\frac{x}{(z+1)^2}\right)\hk
</me>
The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
z+\frac{1}{1+z} &amp; xz &amp; 3xy-\frac{x}{(z+1)^2}
\end{matrix}
\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=(3x-x)\hi
  -\left(3y-\frac{1}{(z+1)^2}-1+\frac{1}{(1+z)^2}\right)\hj +z\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2x\,\hi +(1-3y)\,\hj+z\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
Write
<me>
S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{z=f(x,y)=1-x^2y,\ x^2+y^2\le 1}
</me>
For <m>S</m>, with the upward pointing normal, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\,\dee{S} &amp;=\big(-f_x\,,\,-f_y\,,\, 1\big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\big(2xy\,,\,x^2\,,\, 1\big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
so that
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;=\big\{4x^2y + (x^2-3x^2y) +\overbrace{(1-x^2y)}^{z}\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
and, by Stokes' theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 1}
  \big\{4x^2y + x^2-3x^2y + 1-x^2y\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
So
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 1}
  \big\{x^2+ 1\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
=\pi + \dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 1} x^2\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
To evaluate the final remaining integral, let's switch to polar coordinates.
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 1} x^2\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
&amp;=\int_0^1\dee{r}\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\  \big(r\cos\theta)^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^1 \dee{r}\ r^3\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \cos^2\theta
</mrow>
</md>
Since <md>
<mrow>
\int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{1+\cos(2\theta)}{2}\ \dee{\theta}
=\left[\frac{\theta}{2}+\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}\right]_0^{2\pi}
=\pi
</mrow>
</md>
we finally have
<m>\int_0^1 \dee{r}\ r^3\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \cos^2\theta=\frac{\pi}{4}</m>
and
<me>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
=\pi+\frac{\pi}{4}
=\frac{5\pi}{4}
</me>
For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
<m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m>,
see Example <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2008D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
A simple closed curve <m>C</m> lies in the plane <m>x + y + z = 1</m>.
The surface this curve <m>C</m> surrounds inside the plane <m>x + y + z = 1</m>
has area <m>5</m>. The curve <m>C</m> is oriented in a clockwise direction as
observed from the positive <m>z</m>-axis looking down at the plane
<m>x + y + z = 1</m>.
</p>

<p>Compute the line integral of <m>\vF (x, y, z) = (z^2 , x^2 , y^2)</m> around <m>C</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The fact that the surface is not completely specified is a big hint.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-\frac{10}{\sqrt{3}}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We are to evaluate a line integral around a curve <m>C</m>. We are told that
<m>C</m> is the boundary of a surface <m>S</m> that is contained in the plane
<m>x+y+z=1</m>, but we are not told precisely what <m>C</m> is. So we are going to have to use Stokes' theorem. The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z} \\
z^2 &amp; x^2 &amp; y^2
\end{matrix}
\right]
= 2y\,\hi + 2z\,\hj +2x\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
and, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSimplicit"/>) with
<m>G(x,y,z)=x+y+z</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\dee{S} &amp;= \left|\frac{\vnabla\vG}{\vnabla\vG\cdot\hk}\right|\dee{x}\dee{y}
        =\sqrt{3}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
\hn\,\dee{S} &amp;= \pm \frac{\vnabla\vG}{\vnabla\vG\cdot\hk}\dee{x}\dee{y}
= \pm \big(\hi+\hj+\hk)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
= \pm \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \big(\hi+\hj+\hk)\,\dee{S}
</mrow>
</md>
Because <m>C</m> is oriented in a clockwise direction as
</p>

<sidebyside width="43%">
<image source="pfigs/stokes8"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
observed from the positive <m>z</m>-axis looking down at the plane,
<m>\hn</m> is to point downwards, so that
<me>
\hn\,\dee{S} = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \big(\hi+\hj+\hk)\,\dee{S}
</me>
On <m>S</m> we have <m>x+y+z=1</m>, so that Stokes' theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S (\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_S 2(y\,\hi+z\,\hj+x\,\hk)\cdot
        \left(-\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\right) \big(\hi+\hj+\hk)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\dblInt_S (y+z+x)\,\dee{S}
=-\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}\dblInt_S \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\frac{10}{\sqrt{3}}
</mrow>
</md>
since <m>S</m> has area <m>5</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2008A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>C</m> be the oriented curve consisting of the 5 line segments which
form the paths from <m>(0, 0, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 1, 1)</m>,
               from <m>(0, 1, 1)</m> to <m>(0, 1, 2)</m>,
               from <m>(0, 1, 2)</m> to <m>(0, 2, 0)</m>,
               from <m>(0, 2, 0)</m> to <m>(2, 2, 0)</m>,
           and from <m>(2, 2, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 0, 0)</m>.
Let
<me>
\vF = (-y+e^x\sin x)\,\hi
         +y^4\,\hj
         +\sqrt{z}\tan z\,\hk
</me>
Evaluate the integral <m>\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
We are to evaluate the line integral of a complicated vector field
around a relatively complicated closed curve. (Sketch it!)
That certainly suggests that
we should not try to evaluate the integral directly.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-2</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We are to evaluate the line integral of a complicated vector field
around a relatively complicated closed curve.
That certainly suggests that
we should not try to evaluate the integral directly. To see if
Stokes' theorem looks promising, let's compute the curl
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z} \\
-y+e^x\sin x &amp; y^4 &amp; \sqrt{z}\tan z
\end{matrix}
\right]
=\hk
</mrow>
</md>
That's suggestive. Next we need to find a surface whose boundary is <m>C</m>.
First, here is a sketch of <m>C</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="51%">
<image source="pfigs/OE08A_8"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
We can choose the surface <m>S</m> to be the union of two flat parts:
<ul>
<li>
the quadralateral <m>Q</m> in the <m>yz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
<m>(0,1,1)</m>, <m>(0,1,2)</m> and <m>(0,2,0)</m> and
</li>
<li>
the triangle <m>T</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
<m>(0,2,0)</m> and <m>(2,2,0)</m>.
</li>
</ul>
The normal to <m>Q</m> is <m>-\hi</m> and the normal to <m>T</m> is <m>-\hk</m>. Then Stokes'
theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_Q  \hk\cdot(-\hi)\,\dee{S} + \dblInt_T  \hk\cdot(-\hk)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= - \dblInt_T \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\text{Area}(T)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -\half\overbrace{2}^{\text{base}}\overbrace{2}^{\text{height}}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-2
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2007A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Suppose the curve <m>C</m> is the intersection of the cylinder
<m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m> with the surface <m>z = xy^2</m>, traversed clockwise if
viewed from the positive z-axis, i.e. viewed <q>from above</q>.
Evaluate the line integral
<me>
\int_C  (z + \sin z) \,\dee{x}
      + (x^3 - x^2 y) \,\dee{y}
      + (x \cos z - y) \,\dee{z}
</me>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The integral looks messy. Compute the curl of
<m>\vF</m> to help gauge if Stokes' theorem would be easier.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The integral looks messy. Let's compute the curl of
<me>
\vF = (z + \sin z) \,\hi
      + (x^3 - x^2 y) \,\hj
      + (x \cos z - y) \,\hk
</me>
to help gauge if Stokes' theorem would be easier.
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
z + \sin z &amp; x^3 - x^2 y &amp; x \cos z - y
\end{matrix}
\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\hi +\hj +(3x^2-2xy)\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
That's a lot simpler than <m>\vF</m>.
For the surface <m>z=f(x,y)=xy^2</m>, with downward pointing normal (since <m>C</m> is traversed clockwise)
<me>
\hn\,\dee{S} = -\big(-f_x,-f_y,1\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
=\big(y^2,2xy,-1\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</me>
by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>),
So, writing
<md>
<mrow>
   S&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{z=xy^2,\ x^2+y^2\le 1}
</mrow><mrow>
   D&amp;=\Set{(x,y)}{x^2+y^2\le 1}
</mrow>
</md>
Stoke's theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\dblInt_D\big\{-y^2+2xy -3x^2+2xy\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 1}\big\{3x^2+y^2-4xy\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
To evaluate this integral, switch to polar coordinates.
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=-\int_0^1\dee{r}\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\
           \big\{3r^2\cos^2\theta+r^2\sin^2\theta
              -4r^2\sin\theta\cos\theta\big\}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-4\pi \int_0^1\dee{r}\ r^3 =-\pi
</mrow>
</md>
since
<m>\int_0^{2\pi}\sin\theta\cos\theta\,\dee{\theta}
 =\frac{1}{2}\int_0^{2\pi}\sin(2\theta)\,\dee{\theta}=0</m>
and
<m>\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}
        =\int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}
        =\pi</m>.
(See Example <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.)
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2006A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Evaluate <m>\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}</m> where <m>S</m> is that part
of the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=2</m> above the plane <m>z=1</m>, <m>\hn</m> is the upward
unit normal, and
<md>
<mrow>
\vF(x,y,z) = -y^2\,\hi  +x^3\,\hj + \big(e^x + e^y +z\big)\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</statement>

<hint><p>
The form of the integrand is sugestive.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{3\pi}{4}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Here is a sketch of the part of <m>S</m> in the first octant.
</p>


<sidebyside width="46%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE06A_6"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
The boundary, <m>\partial S</m>, of <m>S</m> is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, <m>z=1</m>, oriented counterclockwise when viewed from above.
It is parametrized by
<me>
\vr(\theta) = \cos\theta\,\hi + \sin\theta\,\hj + \hk
\qquad 0\le \theta\le 2\pi
</me>
So Stokes' theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
  = \oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in = \int_0^{2\pi} \Big(\overbrace{
        -\sin^2\theta\,\hi +\cos^3\theta\,\hj+(\text{mess})\hk
               }^{\vF(\vr(t))}\Big)\cdot
   \big(\overbrace{-\sin\theta\,\hi+\cos\theta\,\hj}^{\vr'(t)}\big)\
     \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_0^{2\pi}\big(\sin^3\theta +\cos^4\theta\big)\,\dee{\theta}
</mrow>
</md>
The integral of any odd power of <m>\sin\theta</m> or <m>\cos\theta</m>
over <m>0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m> is zero.
(See Example <xref ref="eg_stokesD"/>.)
In particular, <m>\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^3\theta\,\dee{\theta} =0</m>.
To integrate <m>\cos^4\theta</m> we use the trig identity
<md>
<mrow>
\cos^2\theta &amp;= \frac{\cos(2\theta)+1}{2}
</mrow><mrow>
\implies
\cos^4\theta &amp;= \frac{\cos^2(2\theta)+2\cos(2\theta) + 1}{4}
</mrow><mrow>
             &amp;= \frac{1}{4}\ \frac{\cos(4\theta)+1}{2}
                +\frac{\cos(2\theta)}{2} +\frac{1}{4}
</mrow><mrow>
             &amp;= \frac{3}{8} + \frac{\cos(4\theta)}{8} + \frac{\cos(2\theta)}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
Finally
<me>
\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\int_0^{2\pi}\Big( \frac{3}{8} + \frac{\cos(4\theta)}{8}
             + \frac{\cos(2\theta)}{2}\Big)\,\dee{\theta}
=\frac{3\pi}{4}
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2005D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let
<me>
\vF = x \sin y\,\hi - y \sin x\,\hj + (x - y)z^2\,\hk
</me>
Use Stokes' theorem to evaluate
<me>
\int_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
</me>
along the path consisting of the straight line segments successively
joining the points <m>P_0 = (0, 0, 0)</m> to <m>P_1 = (\pi/2, 0, 0)</m> to
<m>P_2 = (\pi/2, 0, 1)</m> to <m>P_3 = (0, 0, 1)</m> to <m>P_4 = (0, \pi/2, 1)</m>
to <m>P_5 = (0, \pi/2, 0)</m>, and back to <m>(0, 0, 0)</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We are to evaluate the line integral of a complicated vector field
around a relatively complicated closed curve. That certainly suggests that
we should not try to evaluate the integral directly. As we are to use
Stokes' theorem, let's compute the curl
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
x \sin y &amp; - y \sin x &amp; (x - y)z^2
\end{matrix}
\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-z^2\,\hi-z^2\,\hj -(y\cos x +x\cos y)\hk
</mrow>
</md>
Next we need to find a surface whose boundary is <m>C</m>.
First, here is a sketch of <m>C</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="54%">
<image source="pfigs/OE05D_8"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
We can choose the surface <m>S</m> to be the union of two flat parts:
<ul>
<li>
the rectangle <m>S_x</m> in the <m>xz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
<m>(\frac{\pi}{2},0,0)</m>, <m>(\frac{\pi}{2},0,1)</m> and <m>(0,0,1)</m> and
</li>
<li>
the rectangle <m>S_y</m> in the <m>yz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
<m>(0,0,1)</m>, <m>(0,\frac{\pi}{2},1)</m> and <m>(0,\frac{\pi}{2},0)</m>
</li>
</ul>
The normal to <m>S_x</m> is <m>-\hj</m> and the normal to <m>S_y</m> is <m>-\hi</m>. Then Stokes'
theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{S_x}  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\hj)\,\dee{S}
  + \dblInt_{S_y}  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\hi)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{z}\ z^2
  + \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \dee{y}\int_0^1\dee{z}\ z^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \dee{x}\ \frac{1}{3}
  + \int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \dee{y}\ \frac{1}{3}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{\pi}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2017D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let
<me>
\vF=\left(\frac{2z}{1+y}+\sin(x^2)\,,\,
           \frac{3z}{1+x}+\sin(y^2)\,,\,
           5(x+1)(y+2)\right)
</me>
Let <m>C</m> be the oriented curve consisting of four line segments
from <m>(0,0,0)</m> to <m>(2,0,0)</m>,
from <m>(2,0,0)</m> to <m>(0,0,2)</m>,
from <m>(0,0,2)</m> to <m>(0,3,0)</m>, and
from <m>(0,3,0)</m> to <m>(0,0,0)</m>.
</p>

<p><ol marker="a">
<li>
Draw a picture of <m>C</m>. Clearly indicate the orientation
on each line segment.
</li>
<li>
Compute the work integral <m>\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer>
<p>(a)</p>
<sidebyside width="58%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE17D_4"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
  (b) <m>\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr} = 10</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a) Here is a sketch.</p>

<sidebyside width="58%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE17D_4"/>
</sidebyside>


<p>
(b) We are to evaluate the line integral of a complicated vector field
around a relatively complicated closed curve. That certainly suggests that
we should not try to evaluate the integral directly. Let's try
Stokes' theorem. First, we compute the curl
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
       \frac{2z}{1+y}+\sin(x^2) &amp; \frac{3z}{1+x}+\sin(y^2) &amp; 5(x+1)(y+2)
       \end{matrix} \right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \Big(5(x+1)-\frac{3}{1+x}\Big)\,\hi
  -\Big(5(y+2)-\frac{2}{1+y}\Big)\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in  +\Big(-\frac{3z}{(1+x)^2}+\frac{2z}{(1+y)^2}\Big)\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
Next we need to find a surface <m>S</m> whose boundary is <m>C</m>.
We can choose the surface <m>S</m> to be the union of two flat parts:
<ul>
<li>
the triangle <m>S_x</m> in the <m>xz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
<m>(2,0,0)</m>, and <m>(0,0,2)</m> and
</li>
<li>
the triangle <m>S_y</m> in the <m>yz</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
<m>(0,0,2)</m>, and <m>(0,3,0)</m>
</li>
</ul>
Note that
<ul>
<li>
The normal to <m>S_x</m> specified by Stokes' theorem is <m>-\hj</m>. On <m>S_x</m>
we have <m>y=0</m>, so that <m>\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hj</m> simplifies to
<m>-\big(5(0+2)-\frac{2}{1+0}\big)=-8</m>.
</li>
<li>
The normal to <m>S_y</m> specified by Stokes' theorem is <m>-\hi</m>. On <m>S_y</m>
we have <m>x=0</m>, so that <m>\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hi</m> simplifies to
<m>\big(5(0+1)-\frac{3}{1+0}\big)=2</m>.
</li>
</ul>
So Stokes' theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S  \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{S_x}  \overbrace{\vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\hj)}^{8}\,\dee{S}
  + \dblInt_{S_y}  \overbrace{\vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\hi)}^{-2}\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=8\,\text{Area}(S_x)  -2\,\text{Area}(S_y)
  =8\frac{1}{2}(2)(2) -2\frac{1}{2}(3)(2)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=10
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2004A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Evaluate <m>\displaystyle\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}</m> where
<m>\vF=y\,\hi+2z\,\hj+3x\,\hk</m> and <m>S</m> is the surface <m>z=\sqrt{1-x^2-y^2}</m>,
<m>z\ge 0</m> and <m>\hn</m> is a unit normal to <m>S</m> obeying <m>\hn\cdot\hk\ge 0</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>-\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
 The boundary, <m>\partial S</m>, of <m>S</m> is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>
oriented counter clockwise as usual. It may be parametrized by
<m>\vr(\theta)=\cos\theta\,\hi+\sin\theta\hj</m>, <m>0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m>. By Stokes' theorem
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;=\oint_{\partial S} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
=\int_0^{2\pi}\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)\cdot\diff{\vr}{\theta}(\theta)
       \,\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp; =\int_0^{2\pi}(\sin\theta,0,3\cos\theta)\cdot(-\sin\theta,\cos\theta,0)
        \,\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}
=-\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\,\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\left[\frac{\theta}{2}-\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}\right]_0^{2\pi}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\pi
</mrow>
</md>
For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
<m>\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin^2\theta</m>, see Example
<xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2000D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\cS</m> be the curved surface below, oriented by the outward normal:
<me>
x^2 + y^2 + 2(z-1)^2 = 6,\qquad z\ge 0.
</me>
(E.g., at the high point of the surface, the unit normal is <m>\hk</m>.)
</p>

<p>Define
<me>
\vG = \nabla\times\vF,
\quad\text{where}\quad
\vF = (xz - y^3\cos z)\,\hi + x^3 e^z\,\hj + xyze^{x^2+y^2+z^2}\,\hk.
</me>
Find <m>\dblInt_\cS \vG\cdot \hn\dee{S}</m>.
</p>

</statement>

<answer><p>
<m>24\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The given surface is an ellipsoid centred at <m>(x,y,z)=(0,0,1)</m>.
It caps a curve <m>\cC</m> in the plane <m>z=0</m>, given by <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>.
This is a circle of radius <m>2</m> centred at the origin, oriented
counterclockwise when viewed from the positive <m>z</m>-axis.
</p>

<p><em>Method I <mdash/> double Stokes':</em>
Let <m>\cD</m> denote the plane disk <m>x^2+y^2\le 4</m>, <m>z=0</m>.
Using Stokes' theorem twice gives
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_\cS \vG\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= \dblInt_\cS \nabla\times\vF\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
= \oint_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
= \dblInt_\cD \nabla\times\vF\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \dblInt_\cD \vG\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow>
</md>
Now in <m>\cD</m> we have <m>\hn=\hk</m> and <m>z=0</m>, so on this surface,
<md>
<mrow>
\vG\cdot\hn
= (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\hk
&amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix} 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
\frac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \frac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp; \frac{\partial }{\partial z} \\
(xz - y^3\cos z) &amp; x^3 e^z &amp; xyze^{x^2+y^2+z^2} \end{matrix}\right]_{z=0}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \big[3x^2 e^z + 3y^2\cos z\big]_{z=0}
= 3(x^2+y^2)
</mrow>
</md>
Hence, using polar coordinates,
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_\cS \vG\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= \dblInt_\cD 3(x^2+y^2)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
= 3\int_{\theta=0}^{2\pi} \int_{r=0}^2 (r^2)\,r\,\dee{r}\,\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= 3(2\pi)(4)= 24\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p><em>Method II <mdash/> single Stokes':</em>
By Stokes' theorem
<me>
\dblInt_\cS \vG\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
= \dblInt_\cS \nabla\times\vF\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
= \oint_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
</me>
Parametrize the circle <m>\cC</m> using
<me>
\vr(\theta) = 2\cos\theta\,\hi + 2\sin\theta\,\hj,\qquad 0\le\theta\le 2\pi
</me>
to obtain
<me>
\dee{\vr} = \diff{\vr}{\theta}\,\dee{\theta}
= (-2\sin\theta\,\hi + 2\cos\theta\,\hj)\,\dee{\theta}.
</me>
Then since <m>z=0</m> on <m>\cC</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_\cS \vG\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= \int_{0}^{2\pi}\!\!\big(
\overbrace{-(2\sin\theta)^3\,\hi \!+\! (2\cos\theta)^3\,\hj}^
                                          {\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)}\big)
\cdot \big(\overbrace{-2\sin\theta\,\hi \!+\! 2\cos\theta\,\hj}^{\vr'(\theta)}\big)
 \,\dee{\theta}

</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= 16 \int_{0}^{2\pi}\big(\sin^4\theta + \cos^4\theta\big)\,\dee{\theta}

</mrow>
</md>
By the double angle trig identities
<md>
<mrow>
\cos^2\theta=\frac{1+\cos(2\theta)}{2}\qquad
\sin^2\theta=\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\qquad
</mrow>
</md>
we have
<md>
<mrow>
\sin^4\theta + \cos^4\theta
&amp;=\frac{\big[1-\cos(2\theta)\big]^2}{4}
 + \frac{\big[1+\cos(2\theta)\big]^2}{4}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{2} + \frac{\cos^2(2\theta)}{2}
=\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1+\cos(4\theta)}{4}
</mrow>
</md>
So
<me>
\dblInt_\cS \vG\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
=16\int_{0}^{2\pi} \left(\frac{3}{4}+\frac{1}{4}\cos(4\theta)\right)
                   \,\dee{\theta}
= 16\times\frac{3}{4}\times (2\pi) = 24\pi
</me>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 1999A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
 Let <m>C</m> be a circle of radius <m>R</m> lying in the plane <m>x+y+z=3</m>.
Use Stokes' Theorem to calculate the value of
<me>
\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
</me>
where <m>\vF=z^2\hi+x^2\hj+y^2\hk</m>. (You may use either orientation of the
circle.)
</p>

</statement>

<hint><p>
Let <m>D</m> be the disk in the plane <m>x+y+z=3</m> whose boundary is <m>C</m>.
Suppose that, as <m>(x,y,z)</m> runs over <m>D</m>, <m>(x,y)</m> runs over the
ellipse <m>D_{xy}</m>.
We are told that the area of <m>D</m> is <m>\pi R^2</m>, but we are
not told the area of <m>D'</m>. So it is easier to deal with the
integral <m>\dblInt_D \dee{S}</m> than with the integral
<m>\dblInt_{D'}\dee{x}\dee{y}</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>2\sqrt{3}\pi R^2</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Note that
<me>
\vnabla\times\vF=\det\left|\begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\\
  \frac{\partial }{\partial x}&amp;
        \frac{\partial }{\partial y}&amp;
        \frac{\partial }{\partial z}\\
z^2&amp;x^2&amp;y^2\end{matrix}\right|
=2y\,\hi+2z\,\hj+2x\,\hk
</me>
Let <m>D</m> be the disk in the plane <m>x+y+z=3</m> whose boundary is <m>C</m> and let
<m>\hn=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(\hi+\hj+\hk)</m> be the upward unit normal to <m>D</m>.
If the circle is oriented counterclockwise, when viewed from above,
then, by Stokes' theorem  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_D \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\ \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
\dblInt_D \big(2y\,\hi+2z\,\hj+2x\,\hk\big)\cdot(\hi+\hj+\hk)\ \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\dblInt_D2\overbrace{\big(x+y+z\big)}^{=3\text{ on } D}\ \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\sqrt{3}\dblInt_D \dee{S}
=2\sqrt{3}\pi R^2
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let <m>S</m> be the oriented surface consisting of the top and
four sides of the cube whose vertices are <m>(\pm 1,\pm1,\pm1)</m>, oriented
outward. If <m>\vF(x,y,z)=(xyz,xy^2,x^2yz)</m>, find the flux of
<m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> through <m>S</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{4}{3}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Let <m>S'</m> be the bottom surface of the cube, oriented with
normal <m>\hk</m>. Then, by Stokes' theorem, since <m>\partial S=\partial S'</m>,
<me>
\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\, \dee{S}
=\oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\oint_{\partial S'}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_{S'}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\, \dee{S}
</me>
Since
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{z} \\
                  xyz &amp; xy^2 &amp; x^2yz \end{matrix}\right]
=\big(\cdots\,,\,\cdots\,,\,y^2-xz\big)
</mrow>
</md>
and <m>\hn=\hk</m> on <m>S'</m> and <m>z=-1</m> on <m>S'</m>
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_{S'}\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\, \dee{S}
&amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \dee{x}\int_{-1}^1 \dee{y}\
         \big(\cdots,\cdots,y^2-xz\big)\cdot\hk\Big|_{z=-1}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \dee{x}\int_{-1}^1 \dee{y}\  (y^2+x)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \dee{x}\int_{-1}^1 \dee{y}\  y^2
=2\times 2\int_0^1\dee{y}\ y^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{4}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</solution>

<solution>
<p>
The boundary of <m>S</m> is the square <m>C</m>, with sides <m>C_1</m>, <m>\cdots</m>, <m>C_4</m>,
in the sketch
</p>

<sidebyside width="45%">
<image source="pfigs/cubeS"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
By Stokes' theorem,
<me>
\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\, \dee{S}
=\oint_{C}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
</me>
Parametrize <m>C_1</m> by <m>x</m>. That is, <m>\vr(x)= x\hi - \hj -\hk</m>, <m>-1\le x\le 1</m>.
Since <m>\vr'(x) = \hi</m>, and <m>y=z=-1</m> on <m>C_1</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{C_1}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \vF\big(\vr(x)\big)\cdot\vr'(x)\ \dee{x}
=\int_{-1}^1 \vF\big(\vr(x)\big)\cdot\hi\ \dee{x}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_{-1}^1\overbrace{x(-1)(-1)}^{xyz}\ \dee{x}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=0\qquad\text{(since $x$ is odd)}
</mrow>
</md>
Parametrize <m>C_2</m> by <m>y</m>. That is, <m>\vr(y)= \hi + y\,\hj -\hk</m>, <m>-1\le y\le 1</m>.
Since <m>\vr'(y) = \hj</m>, and <m>x=1</m> on <m>C_2</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{C_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\int_{-1}^1 \vF\big(\vr(y)\big)\cdot\hj\ \dee{y}
=\int_{-1}^1\overbrace{y^2}^{xy^2}\ \dee{y}
=\left[\frac{y^3}{3}\right]_{-1}^1
=\frac{2}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
Parametrize <m>C_3</m> by <m>x</m>. That is, <m>\vr(x)= x\hi + \hj -\hk</m> with <m>x</m> running
from <m>1</m> to <m>-1</m>. (If you're nervous about this, parametrize
by <m>t=-x</m>. That is <m>\vr(t)= -t\,\hi + \hj -\hk</m>, <m>-1\le t\le 1</m>.)
Since <m>\vr'(x) = \hi</m>, and <m>y=1</m>, <m>z=-1</m> on <m>C_3</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{C_3}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\int^{-1}_1\!\! \vF\big(\vr(x)\big)\cdot\hi\ \dee{x}
=\int^{-1}_1\overbrace{x\ (1)(-1)}^{xyz}\ \dee{x}
=0\quad\text{(since $x$ is odd)}
</mrow>
</md>
Parametrize <m>C_4</m> by <m>y</m>. That is, <m>\vr(y)= -\hi + y\,\hj -\hk</m>, with
<m>y</m> running from <m>1</m> to <m>-1</m>. Since <m>\vr'(y) = \hj</m>, and <m>x=-1</m> on <m>C_4</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{C_4}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\int^{-1}_1 \vF\big(\vr(y)\big)\cdot\hj\ \dee{y}
=\int^{-1}_1\overbrace{(-1)y^2}^{xy^2}\ \dee{y}
=-\left[\frac{y^3}{3}\right]^{-1}_1
=\frac{2}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
All together
<me>
\dblInt_S\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\, \dee{S}
=\int_{C_1}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr} + \int_{C_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
 +\int_{C_3}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr} + \int_{C_4}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\frac{4}{3}
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let <m>S</m> denote the part of the spiral ramp (that is helicoidal
surface) parametrized by
<me>
x=u\cos v,\ y=u\sin v,\ z=v\qquad
0\le u\le 1,\ 0\le v\le 2\pi
</me>
Let <m>C</m> denote the boundary of <m>S</m>
with orientation specified by the upward pointing normal on <m>S</m>. Find
<me>
\int_C y\,\dee{x}-x\,\dee{y}+ xy\,\dee{z}
</me>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>-2\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Let's try Stokes' Theorem. Call <m>\vF=y\,\hi-x\,\hj+xy\,\hk</m>. Then
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{z} \\
                  y &amp; -x &amp; xy \end{matrix}\right]
=x\,\hi-y\,\hj-2\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
Now compute <m>\hn\,\dee{S}</m> in the <m>(u,v)</m>-parametrization.
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(u,v)&amp;=\big(u\cos v, u\sin v, v\big)
</mrow><mrow>
\pdiff{\vr}{u}(u,v)&amp;=\big(\cos v, \sin v, 0\big)
</mrow><mrow>
\pdiff{\vr}{v}(u,v)&amp;=\big(-u\sin v, u\cos v, 1\big)
</mrow><mrow>
\pdiff{\vr}{u}\times\pdiff{\vr}{v}
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \cos v &amp; \sin v &amp; 0 \\
                  -u\sin v&amp; u\cos v&amp; 1 \end{matrix}\right]
=\big(\sin v, -\cos v, u\big)
</mrow><mrow>
\hn\,\dee{S}&amp;=\big(\sin v, -\cos v, u\big)\,\dee{u}\,\dee{v}
</mrow>
</md>
Since <m>u\ge 0</m>, we do indeed have the upward pointing normal.
So, Stokes' theorem tells us
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\int_C y\,\dee{x}-x\,\dee{y}+ xy\,\dee{z}
=\int_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_0^1 \dee{u} \int_0^{2\pi} \dee{v}\  \big(u\cos v, -u\sin v, -2\big)
\cdot\big(\sin v, -\cos v, u\big)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_0^1 \dee{u} \int_0^{2\pi} \dee{v}\ \big(2u\sin v\cos v-2u\big)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\left[\int_0^1 \dee{u} \ u\right]
    \left[\int_0^{2\pi} \dee{v}\ \big(\sin 2v-2\big)\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\half(-4\pi)=-2\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup><introduction><application/></introduction>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let <m>C</m> be the intersection of <m>x+2y-z=7</m> and <m>x^2-2x+4y^2=15</m>.
The curve <m>C</m> is oriented counterclockwise when viewed from high on the
<m>z</m>-axis. Let
<me>
\vF=\big(e^{x^2}+yz\big)\,\hi
   +\big(\cos(y^2)-x^2\big)\,\hj
   +\big(\sin(z^2)+xy\big)\,\hk
</me>
Evaluate <m>\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Given the form of <m>\vF</m>, direct evaluation looks hard.
</p>

<p>The integral evaluations can be greatly simplified by using
that the centroid <m>(\bar x,\bar y)</m> of any region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane
is
<me>
\bar x =\frac{\dblInt_R x\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}}{\text{Area}(R)}\qquad
\bar y =\frac{\dblInt_R y\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}}{\text{Area}(R)}
</me>
</p>

</hint>

<answer><p>
<m>24\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Given the form of <m>\vF</m>, direct evaluation looks hard. So let's try
Stokes' theorem, using as <m>S</m> the part of the plane <m>G(x,y,z)=x+2y-z=7</m>
that is inside <m>x^2-2x+4y^2=15</m>. Then
<me>
\hn\,\dee{S} = \pm \frac{\vnabla G}{\vnabla G\cdot\hk}\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
= \pm\big(\hi+2\hj-\hk\big)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</me>
As <m>C</m> is oriented counterclockwise when viewed from high, Stokes'
theorem specifies the upward pointing normal so that
<m>\hn\,\dee{S} = -\big(\hi+2\hj-\hk\big)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}</m>.
</p>

<p>From the observations that
<me>
\vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{z} \\
                  e^{x^2}+yz &amp; \cos(y^2)-x^2 &amp; \sin(z^2)+xy
                  \end{matrix} \right]
=x\,\hi-(z+2x)\,\hk
</me>
and that we can rewrite <m>x^2-2x+4y^2=15</m> as <m>(x-1)^2+4y^2=16</m>,
we have
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{(x-1)^2+4y^2\le 16}\,
     [x\hi-(z+2x)\hk]\Big|_{z=-7+x+2y}\cdot(-1,-2,1)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{(x-1)^2+4y^2\le 16} [-x-(-7+x+2y+2x)]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{(x-1)^2+4y^2\le 16} [7-4x-2y]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
To evaluate the integrals of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> we use that, for any region <m>R</m>
in the <m>xy</m>--plane,
<me>
\bar x =\frac{\dblInt_R x\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}}{\text{Area}(R)}\qquad
\bar y =\frac{\dblInt_R y\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}}{\text{Area}(R)}
</me>
Our ellipse is <m>\frac{(x-1)^2}{4^2}+\frac{y^2}{2^2}=1</m>
and so has area <m>\pi ab = \pi\times4\times 2=8\pi</m> and centroid
<m>(\bar x,\bar y) = (1,0)</m>. So, using
<m>R=\Set{(x,y)}{\frac{(x-1)^2}{4^2}+\frac{y^2}{2^2}\le 1}</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_R [7-4x-2y]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\text{Area}(R) \big\{7-4\bar x-2\bar y\}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=8\pi[7-4\times 1-2\times 0]=24\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2012D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Find the curl of the vector field
<m>\vF  = \big(2 + x^2 + z\,,\, 0\,,\, 3 + x^2 z\big)</m>.
</li>
<li>
Let <m>C</m> be the curve in <m>\bbbr^3</m> from the point <m>(0, 0, 0)</m> to
the point <m>(2, 0, 0)</m>, consisting of three consecutive line segments
connecting the points <m>(0, 0, 0)</m> to <m>(0, 0, 3)</m>,
<m>(0, 0, 3)</m> to <m>(0, 1, 0)</m>, and <m>(0, 1, 0)</m> to <m>(2, 0, 0)</m>.
Evaluate the line integral
<me>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</me>
where <m>\vF</m> is the vector field from (a).
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Part (a) is a hint for part (b). Sketch the curve in part (b).
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\vnabla\times\vF=(1-2xz)\,\hj</m></p><p>
(b) <m>\frac{20}{3}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a)
The curl is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
2+x^2+z &amp;  0 &amp; 3+x^2z
\end{matrix}
\right]
=(1-2xz)\,\hj
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p> (b) We are going to use Stokes' theorem. The specified curve <m>C</m>
is not closed and so is not the boundary of a surface. So we extend
<m>C</m> to a closed curve <m>\tilde C</m> by appending to <m>C</m> the line segment <m>L</m>
from <m>(2,0,0)</m> to <m>(0,0,0)</m>. In the figure below, <m>C</m> is the red curve
and <m>\tilde C</m> is <m>C</m> plus the blue line segment.
</p>

<sidebyside width="44%">
<image source="pfigs/OE12D_4"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
The closed curve <m>\tilde C</m> is boundary of the surface <m>S</m> that is the
union of
<ul>
<li> the triangle <m>T_1</m> in the <m>yz</m>-plane
with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,0,3)</m> and <m>(0,1,0)</m>
and with normal vector <m>-\hi</m> and
</li>
<li> the triangle <m>T_2</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane
with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,1,0)</m> and <m>(2,0,0)</m>
and with normal vector <m>-\hk</m>.
</li>
</ul>
So, by Stokes' theorem
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} + \int_L \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
=  \int_{\partial S} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
= \dblInt_S \vnabla\times \vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in= \dblInt_{T_1} \vnabla\times \vF\cdot(-\hi)\,\dee{S}
  + \dblInt_{T_2} \vnabla\times \vF\cdot(-\hk)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in= \dblInt_{T_1} (1-2xz)\,\hj\cdot(-\hi)\,\dee{S}
  + \dblInt_{T_2} (1-2xz)\,\hj\cdot(-\hk)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=0
</mrow>
</md>
Consequently the integral of interest
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=- \int_L \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
=- \int_2^0 (2+x^2)\,\dee{x}
\quad\text{since } \dee{y}=\dee{z}=z=0  \text{ on } L
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^2 (2+x^2)\,\dee{x}
={\left[2x+\frac{x^3}{3}\right]}_0^2
=\frac{20}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2012D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Let <m>S</m> be the bucket shaped surface consisting of the cylindrical surface
<m>y^2 + z^2 = 9</m> between <m>x = 0</m> and <m>x = 5</m>, and the disc inside the
<m>yz</m>-plane of radius <m>3</m> centered at the origin. (The bucket <m>S</m>
has a bottom, but no lid.) Orient <m>S</m> in such a way that the unit normal
points outward. Compute the flux of the vector field <m>\vnabla\times\vG</m>
through <m>S</m>, where <m>\vG = (x, -z, y)</m>.
</li>
<li>
Compute the flux of the vector field <m>\vF = (2 + z, xz^2 , x \cos y)</m>
through <m>S</m>, where <m>S</m> is as in (a).
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
For practice, evaluate the flux of part (a) twice <mdash/> once by direct
evaluation and once using Stokes' theorem.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>-18\pi</m> </p><p>
(b) <m>-18\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) <em>by direct evaluation:</em>
The curl of <m>\vG</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vG
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
x &amp; -z &amp; y
\end{matrix}
\right]
=2\hi
</mrow>
</md>
The part of <m>S</m> in the first octant is sketched in the figure on the left below.
<m>S</m> consists of two parts <mdash/> the cylindrical surface
<me>
S_1 = \Set{(x,y,z)}{y^2+z^2=9,\ 0\le x\le 5}
</me>
and the disc
<me>
S_2 = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x=0,\ y^2+z^2\le 9}
</me>
The normal <m>\hn</m> to <m>S_1</m> always points radially outward from the cylinder
and so always has <m>\hi</m> component zero. The normal of <m>S_2</m> is <m>-\hi</m>.
So the flux is
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_S \vnabla\times \vG \cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= \dblInt_{S_1} 2\hi \cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
   + \dblInt_{S_2} 2\hi \cdot (-\hi)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -2 \dblInt_{S_2} \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -2 \big(\pi 3^2\big) = -18\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(a) <em>using Stokes' theorem:</em>
Let's use Stokes' theorem. The boundary <m>\partial S</m> of <m>S</m> is the cirlce
<m>y^2+z^2=9</m>, <m>x=5</m>, oriented clockwise when viewed from far down the <m>x</m>-axis.
We'll parametrize it by <m>\vr(\theta)=\big(5, 3\cos\theta, -3\sin\theta\big)</m>.
Then Stokes' theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vG\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;=\oint_{\partial S}\vG\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \big(5\,,\,3\sin\theta,3\cos\theta\big)\cdot
       \big(0\,,\,-3\sin\theta\,,\,-3\cos\theta\big)\,\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \big(-9\sin^2\theta-9\cos^2\theta\big)\,\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-18\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<sidebyside width="33%">
<image source="pfigs/OE12D_6a"/>
<image source="pfigs/OE12D_6b"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
 (b)
This time we'll use the divergence theorem. The surface <m>S</m> is not closed.
So we'll use the auxilary surface formed by <q>topping <m>S</m> off</q>
with the cap <m>T=\Set{(5,y,z)}{y^2+z^2\le 9}</m>. If we give <m>T</m> the normal vector <m>\hi</m>, this auxiliary surface, the union of <m>S</m> and <m>T</m>, is the boundary of
<m>V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{y^2+z^2\le 9,\ 0\le x\le 5}</m>. So the divergence theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_S  \vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
+\dblInt_T \vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= \dblInt_{\partial V} \vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\tripInt_V \vnabla\cdot \vF\ \dee{V}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=0
</mrow>
</md>
since <m>\vnabla\cdot \vF = 0</m>. Thus the flux of interest is
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_S  \vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;=-\dblInt_T \vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=-\dblInt_T \vF\cdot\hi\,\dee{S}
=-\dblInt_T (2+z)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-2\dblInt_T \,\dee{S}
   \qquad\text{since } \dblInt_T z\,\dee{S}=0, \text{ because $z$ is odd}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -18\pi
    \qquad\text{since $T$ has area $9\pi$}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2010D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let
<me>
\vF(x, y, z) = \Big(\frac{y}{x} +x^{1+x^2}\,,\, x^2-y^{1+y^2}\,,\,
                       \cos^5(\ln z)\Big)
</me>
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Write down the domain <m>D</m> of <m>\vF</m>.
</li>
<li><p>
Circle the correct statement(s):
<ol marker="a">
<li> D is connected.
</li>
<li> D is simply connected.
</li>
<li> D is disconnected.
</li>
</ol></p>
</li>
<li>
Compute <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m>.
</li>
<li>
Let <m>C</m> be the square with corners <m>(3 \pm 1, 3 \pm 1)</m> in the plane
<m>z = 2</m>, oriented clockwise (viewed from above, i.e. down <m>z</m>-axis).
Compute
<me>
\int_C \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}
</me>
</li>
<li>
Is <m>\vF</m> conservative?
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
By definition, <m>D</m> is connected if any two points in <m>D</m>
can be joined by a curve that lies completely in <m>D</m>.
</p>

<p>By definition, <m>D</m> is simply connected if any simple closed curve in
<m>D</m> can be shrunk to a point continuously in <m>D</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x \gt 0,\ y \gt 0,\ z \gt 0}</m>
</p>

<p>(b) The domain <m>D</m> is both connected and simply connected.
</p>

<p>(c) <m>\vnabla\times\vF=\big(2x-\frac{1}{x}\big)\hk</m>
</p>

<p>(d) <m>2\ln 2-24</m>
</p>

<p>(e) No. <m>\vF</m> is not conservative.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a)
Since
<ul>
<li>
<m>\frac{y}{x}</m> is defined when <m>x\ne 0</m> and
</li>
<li>
<m>x^{1+x^2}=e^{(1+x^2)\ln x}</m> is defined when <m>\ln x</m> is defined,
which is when <m>x \gt 0</m> (assuming that we are not allowed to use complex numbers)
and
</li>
<li>
<m>y^{1+y^2}=e^{(1+y^2)\ln y}</m> is defined when <m>\ln y</m> is defined,
which is when <m>y \gt 0</m> and
</li>
<li>
<m>\cos^5(\ln z)</m> is defined when <m>\ln z</m> is defined,
which when <m>z \gt 0</m>
</li>
</ul>
the domain of <m>\vF</m> is
<me>
D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x \gt 0,\ y \gt 0,\ z \gt 0}
</me>
</p>

<p> (b) The domain <m>D</m> is both connected (any two points in <m>D</m>
can be joined by a curve that lies completely in <m>D</m>) and
simply connected (any simple closed curve in <m>D</m> can be shrunk to a
point continuously in <m>D</m>).
</p>

<p> (c) The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
\frac{y}{x} +x^{1+x^2} &amp; x^2-y^{1+y^2} &amp; \cos^5(\ln z)
\end{matrix}
\right]
=\big(2x-\frac{1}{x}\big)\hk
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p> (d)
The integrand for direct evaluation looks very complicated.
On the other hand <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> is quite simple. So let's
try Stokes' thoerem.
Denote
<me>
S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{2\le x\le 4,\ 2\le y\le 4,\ z=2}
</me>
The boundary of <m>S</m> is <m>C</m>. Because of the clockwise orientation
of <m>C</m>, we assign the normal vector <m>-\hk</m> to <m>S</m>. See the sketch below
</p>

<sidebyside width="37%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE10D_5"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Then, by Stokes'
theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
= \dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF\cdot(-\hk)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -\dblInt_S \big(2x-\tfrac{1}{x}\big)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -\int_2^4\dee{x}\int_2^4\dee{y}\ \big(2x-\tfrac{1}{x}\big)
 =-\int_2^4\dee{x}\ 2\big(2x-\tfrac{1}{x}\big)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp; = - 2\Big[x^2-\ln x\Big]_2^4
=-2\big[12-\ln 2\big] 
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\ln 2-24
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p> (e) Since <m>\vnabla\times\vF</m> is not <m>\vZero</m>, <m>\vF</m> cannot
be conservative.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2007A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
A physicist studies a vector field <m>\vF(x, y, z)</m>. From experiments,
it is known that <m>\vF</m> is of the form
<me>
\vF(x, y, z) = xz\,\hi + (axe^y z + byz)\,\hj + (y^2 - xe^y z^2 )\,\hk
</me>
for some real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>. It is further known that
<m>\vF = \vnabla\times\vG</m> for some differentiable vector field <m>\vG</m>.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Determine <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
</li>
<li>
Evaluate the surface integral
<me>
\dblInt_S\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</me>
where <m>S</m> is the part of the ellipsoid <m>x^2 + y^2 + \frac{1}{4} z^2 = 1</m>
for which <m>z \ge 0</m>, oriented so that its normal vector has a positive <m>z</m>-component.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Review §<xref ref="sec_vectorPotential"/>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>a=2</m>, <m>b=-1</m></p><p>
(b) <m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a)
By the vector identity <m>\vnabla\cdot\big(\vnabla\times\vG\big)=0</m>
(Theorem <xref ref="thm_degTwoIdentities"/>.a).
So we must have
<md>
<mrow>
0&amp;=\vnabla\cdot\vF
  =\frac{\partial }{\partial x}\big(xz\big)
   + \frac{\partial }{\partial y}\big(axe^y z + byz\big)
   + \frac{\partial }{\partial z}\big(y^2 - xe^y z^2 \big)
</mrow><mrow>
 &amp;= z + \big(axe^y z+bz\big) + \big(-2xe^yz\big)
</mrow><mrow>
 &amp;= (1+b)z + (a-2)x e^y z
</mrow>
</md>
So we need <m>a=2</m> and <m>b=-1</m>.
</p>

<p>(b)
Note that the boundary, <m>\partial S</m>, is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, <m>z=0</m>,
oriented counter-clockwise. Also note that, if we knew what <m>\vG</m> was,
we would be able to use Stokes' theorem to give
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_S\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
&amp;= \dblInt_S(\vnabla\times\vG)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\oint_{\partial S} \vG\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow>
</md>
So let's find a vector potential <m>\vG</m>.
That is, let's try and find a vector field
<m>\vG= G_1\,\hi + G_2\,\hj + G_3\,\hk</m> that obeys <m>\vnabla\times\vG = \vF</m>,
or equivalently,
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{\partial G_3}{\partial y} -\frac{\partial G_2}{\partial z} &amp;= F_1
         =xz
</mrow><mrow>
-\frac{\partial G_3}{\partial x} +\frac{\partial G_1}{\partial z}&amp;=F_2
         =2xe^y z - yz
</mrow><mrow>
\frac{\partial G_2}{\partial x} -\frac{\partial G_1}{\partial y}&amp;=F_3
         =y^2 - xe^y z^2
</mrow>
</md>
Let's also require that <m>G_3=0</m>. (If this is mysterious to you,
review §<xref ref="sec_vectorPotential"/>.)
Then the equations above simplify to
 <md>
<mrow>
 -\frac{\partial G_2}{\partial z} &amp;=xz
</mrow><mrow>
  \frac{\partial G_1}{\partial z} &amp;=2xe^y z - yz
</mrow><mrow>
\frac{\partial G_2}{\partial x} -\frac{\partial G_1}{\partial y}&amp;=y^2 - xe^y z^2
</mrow>
</md>
Now  the first equation contains only a single unknown, namely <m>G_2</m> and we
can find all <m>G_2</m>'s that obey the first equation simply by integrating
with respect to <m>z</m>:
<me>
G_2 = -\frac{xz^2}{2} + N(x,y)
</me>
Note that, because <m>\frac{\partial }{\partial z}</m> treats <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>
as constants, the constant of integration <m>N</m> is allowed to depend on <m>x</m>
and <m>y</m>.
</p>

<p>Similarly, the second equation contains only a single unknown,
<m>G_1</m>, and is easily solved by integrating with respect to <m>z</m>.
The second equation is satisfied if and only if
<me>
G_1 = xe^y z^2 - \frac{1}{2}yz^2 + M(x,y)
</me>
for some function <m>M</m>.
</p>

<p>Finally, the third equation is also satisfied
if and only if <m>M(x,y)</m> and <m>N(x,y)</m> obey
<me>
\frac{\partial }{\partial x}\Big(-\frac{xz^2}{2} + N(x,y)\Big)
-\frac{\partial }{\partial y}\Big(xe^yz^2-\frac{yz^2}{2} + M(x,y)\Big)
     =y^2 - xe^y z^2
</me>
which simplifies to
<me>
\frac{\partial N}{\partial x}(x,y) -\frac{\partial M}{\partial y}(x,y) =y^2
</me>
This is one linear equation in two unknowns, <m>M</m> and <m>N</m>.
Typically, we can easily solve one linear equation in one unknown.
</p>

<p>So we are free to eliminate one of the unknowns by setting, for example,
<m>M=0</m>, and then choosing any <m>N</m> that obeys
<me>
\frac{\partial N}{\partial x}(x,y) = y^2
</me>
Integrating with respect to <m>x</m> gives, as one possible choice, <m>N(x,y) = xy^2</m>. So we have found a vector potential. Namely
<me>
\vG = \Big( xe^y z^2 - \frac{1}{2}yz^2\Big)\,\hi
       +\Big(xy^2  -\frac{xz^2}{2}\Big)\,\hj
</me>
We can now evaluate the flux. Parametrize <m>\partial S</m>
by
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(\theta) &amp; = \cos\theta\,\hi +\sin\theta\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(\theta) &amp; = -\sin\theta\,\hi +\cos\theta\,\hj
</mrow>
</md>
with <m>0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m>.
So
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_S\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
   &amp;=\oint_{\partial S} \vG\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}
   \Big(\overbrace{\cos\theta\sin^2\theta\,\hj}^{\vG(\vr(\theta))}\Big)
    \cdot\overbrace{\big(-\sin\theta\,\hi +\cos\theta\,\hj\big)}^{\vr'(\theta)}
      \  \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2\theta\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\ \frac{1+\cos(2\theta)}{2}\
                         \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{4}\int_0^{2\pi}  \big\{ 1-\cos^2(2\theta)\big\}\
                         \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{4}\int_0^{2\pi}  \Big\{ 1-\frac{1+\cos(4\theta)}{2}\Big\}\
                         \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp; = \frac{1}{4}\ \frac{1}{2}\ 2\pi
    \qquad\text{since } \int_0^{2\pi} \cos(4\theta)\ \dee{\theta}=0
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{\pi}{4}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2006D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>C</m> be the curve in the <m>xy</m>-plane from the point <m>(0, 0)</m> to
the point <m>(5, 5)</m> consisting of the ten line segments consecutively
connecting the points <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(0,1)</m>, <m>(1,1)</m>, <m>(1,2)</m>, <m>(2,2)</m>, <m>(2,3)</m>,
<m>(3,3)</m>, <m>(3,4)</m>, <m>(4,4)</m>, <m>(4,5)</m>, <m>(5,5)</m>. Evaluate the line integral
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow>
</md>
where
<md>
<mrow>
\vF = y\,\hi + (2x - 10)\,\hj
</mrow>
</md>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Considering that there are ten line segments in <m>C</m>,
it is probably not very efficient to use direct evaluation.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-15</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Considering that there are ten line segments in <m>C</m>,
it is probably not very efficient to use direct evaluation.
Two other possible methods come to mind. If <m>\vF</m> is conservative,
we can use <m>\vF</m>'s potential. Even if <m>\vF</m> is not conservative,
it may be possible to efficiently use Stokes' (or Green's) theorem.
So let's compute
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
y &amp; 2x-10 &amp; 0
\end{matrix}
\right]
=\hk
</mrow>
</md>
As <m>\vnabla\times\vF\ne\vZero</m>, the vector field <m>\vF</m> is not conservative.
As <m>\vnabla\times\vF\ne\vZero</m> is very simple, it looks like Stokes'
theorem could provide an efficient way to compute the integral.
The left figure below contains a sketch of <m>C</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="48%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE06D_2"/>
 <image source="pfigs/OE06D_2b"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
The curve <m>C</m> is not closed, and so is not the boundary of a surface,
so we cannot apply Stokes' theorem directly. But we can easily
come up with a surface whose boundary contains <m>C</m>. Let <m>R</m> be the shaded
region in the figure on the right above. The boundary <m>\partial R</m>
of <m>R</m> consists of two parts <mdash/> <m>C</m> and the line segment <m>L</m>.
The normal of <m>R</m> for <m>-\hk</m> (since <m>\partial R</m> is oriented clockwise).
So Stokes' theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF \cdot\dee{\vr} + \int_L \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;= \dblInt_R  \vnabla\times\vF \cdot(-\hk)\ \dee{S}
= \dblInt_R  (\hk) \cdot(-\hk)\ \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= -\text{Area}(R)
</mrow>
</md>
<m>R</m> is the union of <m>5</m> triangles, each of height <m>1</m> and base <m>1</m>.
So
<me>
\text{Area}(R) = 5\times \frac{1}{2}\times 1\times 1
=\frac{5}{2}
</me>
If we denote by <m>-L</m> the line segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(5,5)</m>,
we can parametrize <m>-L</m> by <m>\vr(t) = t(5,5)</m>, <m>0\le t\le 1</m> and
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{-L} \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\int_0^1 \overbrace{\big(5t\,\hi + (10t-10)\,\hj\big)}^{\vF(\vr(t))}
              \cdot\overbrace{(5\,\hi+5\,\hj)}^{\vr'(t)}\ \dee{t}
=\int_0^1 5\big(15t-10\big) \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=25\left(\frac{3}{2}-2\right)
=-\frac{25}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
All together
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;= -\text{Area}(R) - \int_L \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
= -\text{Area}(R) + \int_{-L} \vF \cdot\dee{\vr}
=-\frac{5}{2}-\frac{25}{2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-15
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2005A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vF = \big(\sin x^2\,,\,xz\,,\,z^2\big)</m>.
Evaluate <m>\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> around the curve <m>C</m> of
intersection of the cylinder <m>x^2+y^2=4</m> with the surface <m>z=x^2</m>, traversed
counter clockwise as viewed from high on the <m>z</m>-axis.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Direct evaluation looks hard.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>12\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
If we parametrize the curve as
<me>
x = 2\cos\theta\qquad
y = 2\sin\theta\qquad
z= x^2 = 4\cos^2\theta\qquad
0\le\theta\le 2\pi
</me>
then the term <m>\sin x(\theta)^2\ x'(\theta)</m> in the integral will be
<m>\sin\big(4\cos^2\theta\big)\ (-2\sin\theta)</m>. That looks hard to integrate.
So let's try Stokes' theorem.
The curl of <m>\vF</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
\sin x^2 &amp; xz &amp; z^2
\end{matrix}
\right]
=-x\,\hi +z\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
The curve <m>C</m> is the boundary of the surface
<me>
S = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\le 4,\ z=x^2}
</me>
with upward pointing normal.
For the surface <m>z=f(x,y) = x^2</m>,
(<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>) gives
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\, \dee{S} &amp; = \pm\big[-f_x(x,y)\,\hi - f_y(x,y)\,\hj + \hk\big]\
          \dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
             &amp; = \pm \big[-2x\,\hi+\hk\big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
Since we want the upward pointing normal
<md>
<mrow>
\hn\, \dee{S} &amp; = \big[-2x\,\hi+\hk\big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
So by Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>)
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_S \vnabla\times\vF \cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 4} \big(-x\,\hi + \overbrace{x^2}^{z}\hk\big)\cdot
\big[-2x\,\hi+\hk\big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=3\dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 4} x^2\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
Switching to polar coordinates
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=3\int_0^2\dee{r}\,r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ r^2\cos^2\theta
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=3\left[\int_0^2 r^3\,\dee{r}\right]
           \left[\int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= 3\ \frac{2^4}{4}
       \left[\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{\cos(2\theta)+1}{2}\ \dee{\theta}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= 12\pi
</mrow>
</md>
For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
<m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2 t\ \dee{t}</m> see Example
<xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2005A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Explain how one deduces the differential form
<me>
\vnabla\times\vE = -\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}
</me>
of Faraday's law from its integral form
<me>
\oint_C\vE\cdot\dee{\vr} =
  -\frac{1}{c}\ \diff{ }{t}\dblInt_S\vH\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</me>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Rewrite <m>\oint_C\vE\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> as a surface integral.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
Rewrite <m>\oint_C\vE\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> as a surface integral.  For the details,
see the solution.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
By Stokes' Theorem,
<me>
\oint_C\vE\cdot \dee{\vr}=\dblInt_S(\vnabla\times\vE)\cdot \hn\,\dee{S}
</me>
so Faraday's law becomes
<me>
\dblInt_S\Big(\vnabla\times\vE
+\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}\Big)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}=0
</me>
This is true for all surfaces <m>S</m>. So the integrand, assuming that it is
continuous,  must be zero.
</p>

<p>To see this, let
<m>\vG=\Big(\vnabla\times\vE+\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}\Big)</m>.
Suppose that <m>\vG(\vx_0)\ne 0</m>. Pick a unit vector <m>\hn</m> in the direction
of <m>\vG(\vx_0)</m>. Let <m>S</m> be a very small flat disk centered on <m>\vx_0</m>
with normal <m>\hn</m> (the vector we picked). Then <m>\vG(\vx_0)\cdot\hn \gt 0</m>
and, by continuity, <m>\vG(\vx)\cdot\hn \gt 0</m> for all <m>\vx</m> on <m>S</m>, if we have
picked <m>S</m> small enough.
 Then <m>\dblInt_S\Big(\vnabla\times\vE
    +\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}\Big)\cdot \hn\,\dee{S} \gt 0</m>, which is a contradiction.
So <m>\vG=\vZero</m> everywhere and we conclude that
<me>
\vnabla\times\vE+\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial\vH}{\partial t}=0
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2004A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>C</m> be the curve given by the parametric equations:
<me>
x=\cos t,\
y=\sqrt{2}\sin t,\
z=\cos t,\
0\le t\le 2\pi
</me>
and let
<me>
\vF=z\,\hi+x\,\hj+y^3z^3\,\hk
</me>
Use Stokes' theorem to evaluate
<me>
\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
</me>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
What is <m>x(t)^2+y(t)^2+z(t)^2=2</m>? How is <m>x(t)</m>
relatex to <m>z(t)</m>?
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\sqrt{2}\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The curl of the specified vector field is
<md>
<mrow>
\nabla\times\vF
&amp;=\nabla\times\big(z\,\hi+x\,\hj+y^3z^3\,\hk\big)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
z &amp; x &amp; y^3z^3
\end{matrix}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=3y^2z^3\,\hi+\hj+\hk
</mrow>
</md>
For every <m>t</m>, we have <m>x(t)=z(t)</m> and <m>x(t)^2+y(t)^2+z(t)^2=2</m>.
So the specified curve is the intersection of the plane <m>x=z</m> and the sphere
<m>x^2+y^2+z^2=2</m>. This curve is the boundary of the circular disk
<me>
D = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x=z,\ x^2+y^2+z^2\le 2}
</me>
The curve is oriented so that
<m>\big(x(t),y(t)\big)=\big(\cos t,\sqrt{2}\sin t\big)</m>
runs in the standard (counterclockwise) direction. So the unit normal
to <m>D</m> used in Stokes' theorem has positive <m>\hk</m> component. Since the
plane <m>x-z=0</m> has unit normal <m>\pm\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(1,0,-1)</m>, the unit
normal used in Stokes' theorem is <m>\hn=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(-1,0,1)</m>. By Stokes'
theorem
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_D\nabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\ \dee{S}
=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\dblInt_D(3y^2z^3,1,1)\cdot(-1,0,1)\ \dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\dblInt_D(1-3y^2z^3)\ \dee{S}
</mrow>
</md>
The disk <m>D</m> is invariant under the reflection <m>(x,y,z)\rightarrow(-x,y,-z)</m>.
Since <m>y^2z^3</m> is odd under this reflection, <m>\dblInt_D y^2z^3\ \dee{s}=0</m>
and
<me>
\oint \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\dblInt_D \ \dee{S}
=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}{\rm Area}(D)
</me>
Because the centre of the ball <m>x^2+y^2+z^2\le 2</m> (namely <m>(0,0,0)</m>)
is contained in the plane <m>x=z</m>, the radius of the disk <m>D</m> is the same
as the radius of the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=2</m>. So <m>D</m> has radius <m>\sqrt{2}</m> and
<me>
\oint \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}{\rm Area}(D)
=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\pi{\big(\,\sqrt{2}\,\big)}^2
=\sqrt{2}\pi
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2002A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Use Stokes' theorem to evaluate
<me>
\oint_C z\,\dee{x}+x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{z}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is the  closed curve which is the intersection of the plane <m>x+y+z=1</m>
with the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>. Assume that <m>C</m> is oriented  clockwise
as viewed from the origin.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The intersection of the plane <m>x+y+z=1</m> with the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>
is a circle. Use symmetry to guess the centre of the circle.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{2\pi}{3\sqrt{3}}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The curl of the vector field <m>\vF=z\,\hi+x\,\hj-y\,\hk</m> is
<me>
\vnabla\times\vF=-\hi+\hj+\hk
</me>
The unit normal to the plane <m>x+y+z=1</m>, with positive <m>\hk</m> component as
required by Stokes' theorem in this case, is <m>\hn=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(1,1,1)</m>.
If we denote by <m>D</m> the circular disk <m>x+y+z=1</m>, <m>x^2+y^2+z^2\le 1</m>, then
Stokes' theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Stokes"/>) says
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C z\,\dee{x}+x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{z}=\oint_C \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_D\vnabla\times\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_D(-1,1,1)\cdot\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(1,1,1)\,\dee{S}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}{\rm Area}(D)
</mrow>
</md>
A reasonable guess for the centre of the disk is <m>\frac{1}{3}(1,1,1)</m>.
(This guess is just based on symmetry.) To check
this we just need to observe that it is indeed on the plane <m>x+y+z=1</m>
and that the distance from  <m>\frac{1}{3}(1,1,1)</m> to any point <m>(x,y,z)</m>
obeying <m>x+y+z=1</m> and <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>, namely
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\sqrt{{\Big(x-\frac{1}{3}\Big)}^2+{\Big(y-\frac{1}{3}\Big)}^2
+{\Big(z-\frac{1}{3}\Big)}^2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2-\frac{2}{3}(x+y+z)+\frac{3}{9}}
=\sqrt{1-\frac{2}{3}+\frac{1}{3}}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}
</mrow>
</md>
is the same. This also tells us that <m>D</m> has radius
<m>\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}</m> and hence area <m>\frac{2}{3}\pi</m>. So the specified
line integral is <m>\frac{2\pi}{3\sqrt{3}}</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2018A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>S</m> be the part of the half cone
<me>
z=\sqrt{x^2+y^2},\quad  y\ge 0,
</me>
that lies below the plane <m>z=1</m>.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Find a parametrization for <m>S</m>.
</li>
<li>
Calculate the flux of the velocity field
<me>
\vv=x\,\hi + y\, \hj -2 z\,\hk
</me>
downward through <m>S</m>.
</li>
<li>
A vector field <m>\vF</m> has curl <m>\vnabla\times \vF= x\, \hi + y\, \hj -2 z\,\hk</m>.
On the <m>xz</m>-plane, the vector field <m>\vF</m> is constant with <m>\vF(x,0,z)=\hj</m>. Given this information, calculate
<me>
\int_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr},
</me>
where <m>\cC</m> is the half circle
<me>
x^2+y^2=1,\ z=1,\ y\ge 0
</me>
oriented from <m>(-1,0,1)</m> to <m>(1,0,1)</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Sketch <m>S</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) One possible parametrization is
<m>\vr(r, \theta) = r\cos \theta\, \hi +r\sin \theta\, \hj + r\,\hk</m>
with <m>0\le r\le 1</m>, <m>0\le \theta \le \pi</m>.
</p>

<p>(b) <m>\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>  (a)
We parametrize <m>S</m> in cylindrical coordinates:
<me>
\vr(r, \theta) = r\cos \theta\, \hi +r\sin \theta\, \hj + r\,\hk
             \qquad \text{with } 0\le r\le 1, 0\le \theta \le \pi
</me>
</p>

<p>(b)
We compute
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{\partial \vr}{\partial r}
    &amp;= \cos \theta \,\hi +\sin \theta \,\hj +\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\frac{\partial \vr}{\partial \theta}
    &amp;= -r \sin \theta \,\hi + r\cos \theta \,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\hn\, \dee{S} &amp;= \pm \frac{\partial \vr}{\partial r}\times
                     \frac{\partial \vr}{\partial \theta}
                   \ \dee{r}  \dee{\theta}
         = \pm \big(-r\cos \theta \,\hi - r \sin \theta \,\hj + r \,\hk\big)\,
                   \dee{r} \dee{\theta}
</mrow>
</md>
To calculate the downward flux, we use the minus sign. We find
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_S \vv \cdot \hn\, \dee{S}
&amp; = \int_0^\pi \dee{\theta} \int_0^1 \dee{r}\  (r \cos \theta, r\sin \theta, -2r)\cdot
                   (r\cos \theta, r\sin \theta, -r)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \int_0^\pi \dee{\theta} \int_0^1 \dee{r}\  3 r^2
  = \pi r^3\Big|_{r=0}^1 = \pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(c) <em>Solution 1</em>:
Let <m>\cP</m> be the path along line segments from <m>(1,0,1)</m> to <m>(0,0,0)</m>
and from <m>(0,0,0)</m> to <m>(-1,0,1)</m>. Here is a sketch. <m>\cP</m> is
in blue.
</p>

<sidebyside width="43%">
  <image source="pfigs/halfCone"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Then
<me>
\int_\cC \vF \cdot \dee{\vr} + \int_\cP \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}
= \dblInt_S \vnabla \times \vF \cdot \hn\, \dee{S}
</me>
by Stokes' Theorem. Along <m>\cP</m>, the vector field <m>\vF</m> is orthogonal
to the curve so that <m>\int_\cP \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m>. Note that
<m>\nabla\times \vF</m> is the vector field <m>\vv</m> from part (b).
Thus
<me>
\int_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr} = \dblInt_S \vv \cdot \hn\, \dee{S} = \pi
</me>
</p>

<p>(c) <em>Solution 2:</em>
Let <m>\cL</m> be the  line segment from <m>(1,0,1)</m> to <m>(-1,0,1)</m> and
let
<md>
<mrow>
\cR=\set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\le1, y\ge 0, z=1}
</mrow>
</md>
Here is a sketch. <m>\cL</m> is in blue and <m>\cR</m> is shaded.
</p>

<sidebyside width="47%">
  <image source="pfigs/halfConeB"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Then
<me>
\int_\cC \vF \cdot \dee{\vr} + \int_\cL \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}
= \dblInt_{\cR} \vnabla \times \vF \cdot (-\hk)\, \dee{S}
</me>
by Stokes' Theorem. Along <m>\cL</m>, the vector field <m>\vF=\hj</m> is orthogonal
to the curve (which has direction <m>-\hi</m> so that <m>\int_\cL \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m>. Note that
<m>\nabla\times \vF</m> is the vector field <m>\vv</m> from part (b).
Thus
<me>
\int_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr} = -\dblInt_\cR \vv \cdot \hk\, \dee{S}
= \dblInt_\cR 2z \, \dee{S}
= 2\dblInt_\cR \, \dee{S}
=2\,\text{Area}(\cR)
= \pi
</me>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Consider <m>\dblInt_S(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,dS</m> where <m>S</m>
is the portion of the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m> that obeys <m>x+y+z\ge 1</m>, <m>\hn</m>
is the upward pointing normal to the sphere and
 <m>\vF=(y-z)\hi+(z-x)\hj+(x-y)\hk</m>. Find another
surface <m>S'</m> with the property that <m>\dblInt_S(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\dblInt_{S'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}</m> and evaluate
<m>\dblInt_{S'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
You can avoid evaluating any integral
by identifying <m>S'</m> as a simple geometric figure.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Let <m>S'</m> be the portion of <m>x+y+z=1</m> that is inside the sphere
<m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>. Then <m>\partial S=\partial S'</m>, so, by  Stokes' theorem,
(with <m>\hn</m> always the upward pointing normal)
<me>
\dblInt_{S'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\oint_{\partial S'}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\oint_{\partial S}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_{S}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
</me>
As
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF=\det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi &amp; \hj &amp; \hk \\
                  \pdiff{}{x} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{y} &amp;
                  \pdiff{}{z} \\
                  y-z &amp; z-x &amp; x-y \end{matrix}\right]
=-2(\hi+\hj+\hk)
</mrow>
</md>
and, on <m>S'</m>,
<m>\hn=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(\hi+\hj+\hk)</m>
<me>
\dblInt_{S'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=\dblInt_{S'}\big(-2\sqrt{3}\big)\,\dee{S}
=-2\sqrt{3}\times{\rm Area}(S')
</me>
<m>S'</m> is the intersection of a plane with a sphere and so is a circular disk. It's center <m>(x_c,y_c,z_c)</m> has to obey
<m>x_c+y_c+z_c=1</m>. By symmetry, <m>x_c=y_c=z_c</m>, so <m>x_c=y_c=z_c=\frac{1}{3}</m>.
Any point, <m>(x,y,z)</m>, which satisfies both <m>x+y+z=1</m> and <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>,
obeys
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\left(x-\frac{1}{3}\right)^2+\left(y-\frac{1}{3}\right)^2
+\left(z-\frac{1}{3}\right)^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=x^2+y^2+z^2-\frac{2}{3}(x+y+z)+3\frac{1}{9}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=1-\frac{2}{3} +\frac{1}{3}=\frac{2}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
That is, any point on the boundary of <m>S'</m> is a distance <m>\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}</m>
from <m>\big(\frac{1}{3}\,,\,\frac{1}{3}\,,\,\frac{1}{3}\big)</m>.
So the radius of <m>S'</m> is <m>\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}</m>,
the area of <m>S'</m> is <m>\frac{2}{3}\pi</m> and
<me>
\dblInt_{S'}(\vnabla\times\vF)\cdot\hn\,\dee{S}
=-2\sqrt{3}\times{\rm Area}(S')
=-\frac{4}{\sqrt{3}}\pi
</me>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise></exercisegroup>

